<HEADLINE> 3 People Injured in Street Clashes in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Three people were injured, one of
them a 13-year-old boy, in overnight street clashes in two
Northern Ireland towns, according to BBC television reports today.
</P>
<P>
The clashes flared late Saturday in the town of Lurgan south of
Belfast in County Armagh, when a crowd attacked an Army patrol
with stones.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers responded by firing plastic bullets at the crowd.
</P>
<P>
In another violent incident, two men received head injuries,
one of them seriously, in a clash between pro-British Protestants
and pro-Irish Catholics in the neighboring town of Portadown.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been high recently in the British province as the
Irish Republican Army, which has been fighting to end British rule
in Northern Ireland, stepped up their violent activities in the
run-up to Britain's general election on May 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
