<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian presidential press office Saturday spoke
highly of the results achieved by Russia and China during Chinese
President Jiang Zemin's five-day state visit here. "the
Sino-Russian relations is playing a positive role in safeguarding
stability in the world and has become a model for state-to-state
ties after the Cold War," it said in a statement released prior to
the conclusion of Jiang's visit.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak returned home Sunday
afternoon from a Gulf tour that took him to Kuwait and Saudi
Arabia to discuss the stalled Mideast peace process. But he made
no statement upon his return. On Sunday he discussed the
coordination of Arab stances in the Mideast peace process with
Saudi King Fahd.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The Irish Republican Army (IRA) admitted on Sunday
planting the bomb which exploded under an electricity pylon near
the British motorway M6 in central England on Friday, a BBC
television report said. The bomb alert early last Friday led to
the closure of M6, one of the country's busiest motorways,
disrupting traffic over a wide area. It was the latest in a series
of attempts by the IRA to disrupt communications on the mainland
in the run-up to the general election on May 1.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia will try its best to enter into the World
Trade Organization (WTO) as early as possible, Russian First
Deputy Prime Minister Anatoly Chubais said Sunday before leaving
for talks with G-7 officials in Washington. He said there are some
economic and political obstacles in the way of Russia's entry into
the WTO.
</P>
<P>
ROME -- An Austrian troop composed of 65 soldiers, 25 vehicles
and four containers of material arrived Saturday at the major
central port of Durres, Albania, to join in the Italy-led
Multinational Protection Force (MPF).
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Opposition Labor Party leader Tony Blair looks set to
enter Downing Street on May 1 with the largest parliamentary
majority held by any party since the Second World War, opinion
polls suggested. The polls in three British Sunday newspapers gave
Labor a lead ranging from 15 to 24 points, implying a minimum of
more than 400 Labor MPs in the 659-seat House of Commons and a
parliamentary majority approaching 200.
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien is expected
today to call a federal election for June 2. Chretien is scheduled
to convene a final cabinet meeting in the morning and then meet
Governor General Romeo LeBlancd to formally request dissolution of
Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
