<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Celebrates National Freedom Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 27 (Xinhua) -- South Africa today
celebrated the third anniversary of National Freedom Day with the
state leaders vowing to spare no efforts to develop national
economy and improve people's life.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a mass rally in Upington, Northern Cape Province,
Mandela said the new constitution promulgated in 1994 was the
cornerstone of the new South African patriotism, and the
framework for undoing the legacy of the country's divided past.
</P>
<P>
"We can say with confidence that the foundation for a better
life has been laid," said Mandela at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"We take immense pride and joy in the fact that since April
27, 1994, millions have for the first time experienced access to
clean water, electricity, housing subsidies, free health care,
nutrition programs and land," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to an increase of criminal offenses, Mandela urged
every community and sector of society to join hands with the
police to defeat crime.
</P>
<P>
To eliminating crime, it is necessary to improve the living
conditions and eradicate poverty. In turn, that would be made
possible by the success of the country's economic policies,
Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki also called on the whole nation
to join hands and wage a struggle against poverty, hunger and
under-development.
</P>
<P>
The struggle should be aimed at strengthening the government's
efforts in addressing problems and challenges brought about by
many years of apartheid, Mbeki said at a rally in Delareyville,
North West Province.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there is also need to wage a struggle against
crimes, such as rape, murder and violence against women, Mbeki
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
