<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Rules Out President's Immediate Visit to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Embassy sources ruled out
that President Suleyman Demirel would visit Egypt within the
coming few days, just hours before the projected visit takes
place, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Demirel's trip here, originally scheduled for Monday, has
been a much-publicized event across the Egyptian press for the
past week.
</P>
<P>
MENA quoted Turkish Ambassador Bashir Yakbes as attributing the
cancellation of the impending summit between Demirel and his
Egyptian counterpart Hosni Mubarak to their over-spilling agendas.
</P>
<P>
"Contacts are under way to fix a date of the projected visit in
the light of their engagements," the Turkish ambassador added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, however, is quick to play down the suspicions around
the last-minute announcement, which coincided with an upcoming
visit of Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Yakbes said that the Israeli minister's visit will not
affect Ankara's ties with Cairo.
</P>
<P>
"Turkish-Israeli ties are an independent matter and will never
affect Turkish-Egyptian relations," the ambassador said in press
statements published in Riyadh today.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the resolutions taken by the Organization of Islamic
Conference in Islamabad on reviewing Islamic states' relations
with Israel, he said Turkey is committed to Islamic summit's
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey has not taken any new step in cooperation with Israel,"
he said, adding that Turkey is just maintaining limited relations
with Israel, which are known to all Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai's trip follows Israel's Foreign Minister David Levy's
two-day visit to Ankara in early April. Levy asserted that ties
between the two countries had grown closer in spite of a frosty
reception from Turkey's Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to make peace with Israel but
ties remain cool. Stalled Mideast peace process added tensions to
the strained ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
