<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Hosts International Trade Arbitration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 27 (Xinhua) -- A three-day international
conference on trade arbitration opened today in Kuwait amid
increased international attention to arbitration aiming to settle
trade and investment disputes.
</P>
<P>
The conference, held for the fist time in Kuwait, will address
themes such as arbitration and effect on encouragement of
investments by attracting capital inflows, role in settlement of
disputes, as well as the system of arbitration in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech to the conference, Kuwaiti Minister of
Justice, Awqaf and Islamic Affairs Mohammed Dhaifallah Sharar
underlined the importance of the conference in view of increased
attention given to arbitration as means of settling trade and
investment disputes.
</P>
<P>
He said Kuwait's decision to host the conference "stems
from its belief that economic development is the strongest way
of providing peace and stability to nations."
</P>
<P>
More than 60 jurists and experts from the U.S., Britain, France,
Germany, Denmark, Norway and Arab and Gulf countries took part
in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ways of fostering Arab cooperation in the field of arbitration
will also be discussed on sidelines of the meeting, conference
sources said.
</P>
<P>
An arbitration center is expected to be set up in Kuwait to
arbitrate local disputes.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is one of the 40 countries which co-founded the
Cairo Center for International Trade Arbitration in July 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
