<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 50,000 People Call for New Bar-On Inquiry in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Organizers of a petition to
set up a state commission of inquiry to probe the Bar-On affair
said today that they have already collected 50,000 signatures.
</P>
<P>
According to an Israel Radio report, Leah Rabin, widow of late
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, and her son Yuval Rabin have added
their names to the list of the petition this morning.
</P>
<P>
The organization for the petition was founded last week soon
after Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein and State Attorney Edana
Arbel announced their decision not to indict Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu for lack of sufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the police team investigating the Bar-On affair had
recommended that Netanyahu be charged with fraud and breach of
trust in the process of appointing of Roni Bar-On as
attorney-general.
</P>
<P>
Former attorney-general Michael Ben-Yair said that only such a
state commission, headed by a Supreme Court justice, could
provide the public with the whole truth of what took place in the
affair.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the police investigation was not able to
probe the civic aspects of the affair, which were the most
important aspects.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, former prime minister and opposition leader Shimon
Peres also signed the petition. He reiterated his demand that
Netanyahu resign immediately and call new elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
