<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian PM Calls Federal Election on June 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien announced today that a federal election will be held on
June 2.
</P>
<P>
Chretien made the announcement after formally requesting
Governor General Romeo LeBlanc to dissolve the Parliament and drop
the writ for the 36-day campaign.
</P>
<P>
The election call came three and a half years in the five-year
mandate of the Liberal Government, which swept to power in
October, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Chretien said that his Liberal Party needs a new mandate to
build on its successes, such as deficit reduction, and prepare the
country better for a new century.
</P>
<P>
"Canadians must now decide what kind of country they want to
build with the hard-won dividend that will be there from our
collective effort to restore health to our public finances,"
Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
Jobs and national unity will become the two dominant issues of
the campaign, which involves more than a dozen of parties, but
mainly the Liberals, the Progressive Conservatives, the Reform
Party, the New Democrats and Bloc Quebecois.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls over the past week suggest that the Liberals
enjoy a commanding lead, anywhere from 22 to 40 percentage points
ahead of their nearest competitor the Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
That would ordinarily all but guarantee a second majority for
Chretien, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
Yet, they also stressed that given so many unpredictables in
campaigns, it's very difficult to foresee how it will all play
out.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Liberal Party won a landslide in the 1993 federal
election, scooping 177 seats in the then 295-member House of
Commons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
