<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> James Baker Visits West Sahara Refugee Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations envoy for West
Sahara and former United States Secretary of State James Baker
today visited the Sahara refugee camps sheltering people from West
Sahara in the Algerian border town of Tindouf.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) said that Baker was scheduled to
meet with the leaders of the Polisario Front to discuss with them
the means to relaunch the West Sahara peace process, stalled for
five years since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Tindouf is the last leg of Baker's North African
fact-collecting tour, which has already brought him to Rabat,
Algiers and Nouakchott, on his first visit to the region since
being nominated special envoy by United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan in March.
</P>
<P>
Baker said in Algiers on Saturday that his tour was essentially
aimed at making an accessment of the situation in West Sahara, and
that he would write a report on his tour to Annan.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted Polisario leaders as saying in a communique that
they were glad to receive Baker and that they were ready to work
with him "to mark out the road of peace."
</P>
<P>
The Polisario also reaffirmed its attachment to the plan by the
United Nations and the Organization of African Unity (OAU) to
organize a self-determination referendum in West Sahara on the
basis of the 1974 census of the local population by Spain, the
former colonial power of the territory.
</P>
<P>
"This census is the only basis for the determination of the
electoral body," said the Polisario. "The plan of solution of the
United Nations and OAU, fruit of long negotiations, remains the
only compromise to which the two parties have subscribed because
it represents a framework of just, pacific and democratic
solution." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
