<HEADLINE> China Trounces Japan at Asian Women's Basketball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Defending Champions China routed
Japan 97-77 at the opening game of the group A at the 17th Asian
Women's Basketball Championship which got underway here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Paced by their 2.04-meter taller center Zheng Haixia, who has
been drafted by the Los Angeles Sparks of WNBA, the taller Chinese
players dominated the game with tough defense and sharp shootings
and built a 46-33 lead at the interval.
</P>
<P>
In other group A games played on Sunday, South Korea beat
Chinese Taipei 88-77, Thailand edged Kyrgyzstan 83-79.
</P>
<P>
In two group B games, Kazakhstan downed India 66-54 and Hong
Kong whitewashed Sri Lanka 82-34.
</P>
<P>
The championship are divided into two groups of round-robin
contests. The top four finishers in group A qualify for the
semifinals while the sixth and last team dropped into the lower
class group B for next championships.
</P>
<P>
The top team from the group B will upgraded to group A. Other
teams in group B are Malaysia, Indonesia, and Macao.
</P>
<P>
The final top three team of group A will represent Asia in the
1998 women's world basektball championships in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
