<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-27 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak: Mideast Peace In Unprecedented Stalemate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said today the Mideast situation has reached "an unprecedented
state of stalemate" because of Israel's insistence on building new
settlement in Arab land.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak made the statements to chief editors of Egyptian
newspapers accompanying him on his return trip from Saudi Arabia,
at the end of his two-nation Gulf tour to coordinate Arab stances
on the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu still persists in
his intransigent stance which led to this condition... while the
U.S. efforts to break this deadlock have not yet achieved any
definite result," he deplored.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming the recent U.N. General Assembly resolution
incriminating Israeli settlements in Jerusalem, Mubarak regretted
that "nothing is achieved in the end despite an overwhelming
majority against the Israeli practices.
</P>
<P>
"This will lead to imbalance in the international relations and
a state of chaos in the international order that is detrimental to
everybody's interests," he warned.
</P>
<P>
It would eventually encourage terrorism and violence, he added.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, approved Thursday by a U.N. General Assembly
emergency session in a vote of 134-3, demands an immediate halt to
Israel's settlement buildings in Arab land and recommends an end
to all forms of assistance for such activities.
</P>
<P>
A day later, Mubarak proposed to host a summit grouping
Jordan's King Hussein, Palestinian President Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu to reactivate peace.
</P>
<P>
But he said Israel has to stop building the Har Homa
neighborhood first, which has brought the peace talks to a halt.
</P>
<P>
"My readiness should be preceded by a clear-cut and definite
Israeli stance on stopping the construction of new Jewish
settlement in disputed Arab East Jerusalem," Mubarak told the
chief editors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said he opposed holding an Arab summit, which
"requires lengthy preparation and great efforts," as well as a
well-defined objective, which is lacking now.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said he discussed with the emir of Kuwait and Saudi
King Fahd during the trip the contacts he has held recently in
this respect.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is also expected to meet with Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad here in a few days, as a completion to the talks he had
with Arab leaders in a bid to salvage the peace march.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
