<HEADLINE> Arafat Calls on Israel to Implement Oslo Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat today reiterated his demand that the current Israeli
government should implement the Oslo Accords signed between Israel
and the PLO.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remark at a joint press conference with
Israeli Labor Member of Knesset (parliament) Yossi Beilin in
Jericho this afternoon. Arafat charged that Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu is not willing to make peace with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader also accused the current Israeli
government of continuing to obstruct the peace process and of
destroying all the agreements signed between Israel and the PLO.
</P>
<P>
Beilin, one of the architects of the Oslo Accords, discussed
with Arafat a plan to revive the stalled peace process. He called
on both the Netanyahu government and the Palestinian National
Authority to build new foundations for the resumption of the peace
process, with the participation of the U.S., the European Union,
Egypt and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Beilin, who is running for the leadership of the Labor Party,
said that he will bring the proposals to the government.
</P>
<P>
Later, he briefed Miguel Angel Moratinos, EU special envoy to
the Middle East peace process, on his meeting with Arafat. The EU
representative praised the proposals, saying that they were
compatible with the European initiative in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, now on a tour of Palestinian self-rule cities in the
West Bank, arrived at Jenin later this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the U.N. General Assembly adopted a
resolution Saturday condemning Israel for its construction of a
new settlement on Jabal Abu Ghneim (Har Homa). He added that it is
a most important resolution which will help pressure Israel to
change its settlement policy in the Palestinian territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
