<HEADLINE> German Police Track Down Airport Blackmailer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 27 (Xinhua) -- German police authorities have
tracked down on the Internet a blackmailer who threatened to
sabotage passenger airliners unless he was paid 50 million German
marks (30 million U.S. dollars), a German newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bild am Sonntag newspaper, the blackmailer
sent in March letters to 15 German airports threatening to steer a
remote-controlled model plane into jet turbines of an airliner
with several hundreds passengers on board as it took off.
</P>
<P>
Because the blackmailer conducted all the later negotiations
through the Internet computer network with his own E-mail address,
investigators managed to track him down in the area of Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
Further probe into the case found out that the suspected
offender was a 25-year-old computer freak who was in heavy debt
and had already been detained by police earlier for tax evasion,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
