<HEADLINE> US President Promotes Volunteerism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Sunday opened a summit on volunteerism, promising the government
will help millions of children learn to read.
</P>
<P>
Clinton went to Philadelphia to open the three-day Presidents'
Summit for America's Future, an ambitious effort with former
Presidents Bush, Carter and Ford to urge more Americans to
volunteer for charity work.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he wanted "to redefine the meaning of citizenship
in America....You have to serve in your community to help make it
a better place," according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
"We're still losing too many kids to crime, to drugs....and
we're here because we don't think we have to put up with it and we
believe together we can change it."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the Defense and Transportation departments would
each "mentor, tutor and teach 1 million children."
</P>
<P>
He also said the government would "adopt" 2,000 schools and
find 1 million reading tutors to ensure American school children
can read independently by third grade.  
