<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Assad Review Regional Developments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today had a phone conversation with Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad on the setbacks to the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The phone conversation comes within the framework of Arab
contacts held by Mubarak to coordinate Arab stands vis-a-vis the
situation in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace talks have stalled after Israel's
construction last month of a new Jewish settlement in the disputed
Arab sector of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli talks have frozen since February 1996. The
Israeli government refuses to return the Golan Heights for a peace
deal with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is expected to meet with al-Assad here in a few days,
as a completion to the talks he had with Arab leaders in a bid to
salvage the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said today the Mideast situation has reached "an
unprecedented state of stalemate" because of Israel's insistence
on building new settlement in Arab land.
</P>
<P>
He made the statements to chief editors of Egyptian newspapers
accompanying him on his return trip from Saudi Arabia, at the end
of his two-nation Gulf tour to coordinate Arab stances on the
stalled peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
