<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Li Peng on Soil and Water Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng called
for more concrete efforts to stop the country's expanding soil
erosion, in a letter to a national conference on soil and water
conservation held here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that that it is a long-term task for China to fight
against soil erosion, to keep a sustainable growth of the economy.
</P>
<P>
"China has a vast population, but the arable land resources are
quite limited," he wrote in the letter, "and it is of great
importance for Chinese people's survival and development to bring
soil erosion under control".
</P>
<P>
According to sources at the conference, the total of eroded
land that China has tackled in a comprehensive way has reached
about 700,000 sq km over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
But the country's overall situation of soil and water
conservation nationwide has continued to worsen at the same time,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese legislators have worked out laws on water and soil
conservation in order to improve the Chinese people's awareness of
the importance of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li said that governments at all levels should help the
poor farmers to get rid of poverty, and keep a close eye on
environmental protection at the same time.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier also urged governments at all levels to
take more measures to tighten the supervision of soil and water
conservation, and implement the country's laws on soil and water
conservation in a serious way.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun attended the meeting today and gave
a speech.  
</P>
</TEXT>
