<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's New Committee for Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China today established a
consultancy committee composed of noted agricultural experts, in an
effort to more effectively resolve problems concerning agriculture
and the rural economy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The committee, whose establishment was supported by the
government ministries and agencies concerned with agriculture,
forestry, water conservancy, meteorology and internal trade, and
scientific academies, consists of 33 leading experts in
relevant fields.
</P>
<P>
The tasks of the committee include offering opinions and
suggestions on the major issues and possible problems in
agriculture and rural economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The experts are also charged with the duty of putting forward
opinions and views on policy-making concerning scientific
development and reform in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to air their views on important science and
technology policies, scientific plans and projects, and
international agricultural cooperation, among others.
</P>
<P>
The experts will also closely follow the latest developments in
agriculture and rural science and technology worldwide, and offer
suggestions as to how China can apply these developments.
</P>
<P>
The committee's first working meeting, scheduled to open
shortly, will focus on key technology China will need to feed a
population of 1.6 billion in the 21st century and on China's
policies concerning science and technology in the
countryside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Lauds Achievements in Asia-Pacific Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the United
Nations Kofi Annan today lauded achievements made in the
Asia-Pacific region over the past half-century, as ministers from
members of the Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the
Pacific (ESCAP) were meeting here to discuss the future for the
region.
</P>
<P>
"During the past half-century, the Asia-Pacific region has
witnessed a range of dramatic changes: economic, social and
political. It has made remarkable gains in human development,"
Annan said in a message to the opening session of the 53rd
ministerial conference of ESCAP.
</P>
<P>
"Particularly in the last two decades, it has emerged as the
most rapidly growing region of the world, with a consistently
rising level of per capita income," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And most recently, many economies in the region, thanks to
their dynamism and openness to foreign investment, have attracted
high levels of capital inflow.
</P>
<P>
"The result has been impressive technological progress,
continued economic advances and increasing integration into the
global economy.
</P>
<P>
"This is a laudable record of which the countries of the region
and ESCAP should be proud," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Annan pointed out that there are still the largest
portion of poor population in the world living in the Asia-Pacific
region and conditions conducive to sustained the economic growth
is not yet in place in many countries.
</P>
<P>
"The greatest challenges ahead is thus to ensure that the
economic and social dynamism that characterizes some parts of the
region spreads throughout the region, and that all segments of
society contribute to, and share in the benefits of, growth and
development," he said.
</P>
<P>
"ESCAP has a key role to play as a catalyst and facilitator in
this process,' he added.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a policy statement at the opening, Adrianus Mooy,
executive secretary of ESCAP, also said that ESCAP may be rightly
proud of its considerable achievements during the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
However, Mooy noted that a great deal remains to be done, and
greatest challenges are yet to be faced in the next century.
</P>
<P>
"We shall be debating and exchanging our views on the
challenges and opportunities for ESCAP, in preparing ourselves on
how best to meet those challenges and opportunities, and indeed in
finding the best and most appropriate commission structure to
address all the issues and problems of the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh today delivered an
inaugural address to the session, also spoke highly of ESCAP's
contribution to the region.
</P>
<P>
Through the good and bad times over the past 50 years, ESCAP
has made significant contribution to Asia's development, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Quietly, yet effectively, I has addressed some of the most
important issues affecting the well-being of millions in the
region -- issues such as poverty alleviation, public health and
agriculture," he said.
</P>
<P>
Among those attending the session are ministers from about 50
of ESCAP's 59 members and associate members and representatives of
other UN agencies and international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which focuses discussions on the challenges and
opportunities facing the ESCAP region while reviewing the ESCAP's
achievements over the past five years, is scheduled to close on
April 30.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Tighter Emission Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The European Parliament has urged
European Union (EU) states to introduce strict measures to control
vehicle emissions.
</P>
<P>
The parliament's committee on environmental affairs proposed a
radical reduction in the permitted ceilings for suspended
particles, essentially sulfur, in gas and diesel fuel, the ANSA
news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The particles are measured in parts per million, or ppm. The
European Commission now allows 220 ppm for petrol and 350 ppm for
diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
The committee said the ceilings should be reduced to 50 ppm,
for both types of fuel.
</P>
<P>
The committee's proposals, based on joint research with auto
makers and fuel suppliers, also suggest that all cars should be
fitted with electronic on-board diagnostic systems designed to
produce cleaner emission fumes.
</P>
<P>
A further proposal is that all cars on roads in the EU consume
no more than 4.5 to 5 liters of fuel per 100 kilometers by the
year 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
