<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK People Support Amendment Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Many local associations have
issued statements or sent groups to the Chief Executive's Office
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) to express
their support to the office's proposals on the amendments to two
ordinances.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the suggestions from the office on the
amendments to the Societies Ordinance and the Public Order
Ordinance have reflected the realities of Hong Kong and they will
do good to Hong Kong's stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the Chief Executive's Office issued a
consultative document to solicit opinions and suggestions from the
communities on its proposals on the amendments to the Societies
Ordinance and the Public Order Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
The proposals were made by the office in line with the
resolution of the Standing Committee of China's National People's
Congress that major amendments to the Societies Ordinance and the
Public Order Ordinance introduced in 1992 and 1995 respectively
shall not be adopted as the laws of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
According to the Information and Public Relations Section of
the Chief Executive's Office, hundreds of Hong Kong-based
associations had handed in letters for approval of the proposals
on the amendments to the ordinances.
</P>
<P>
They also raised constructive ideas including suggestions of
revisions or requirements for further clarification on some
specific terms, an official of the section said.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here today, Cheng Yiu-tong, chairman of
the Hong Kong Federation of Trade Unions, said that his federation
stood for the proposals on the amendments to the two ordinances.
</P>
<P>
He said that the proposals have absorbed the concept of
"national security", which is consistent with the Basic Law and
the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR).
</P>
<P>
He said that the proposal for prohibiting local political
organizations from establishing foreign ties is to prevent foreign
political forces from interfering in political operations in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Herbert Liang, chairman of the Chinese Manufacturer's
Association of Hong Kong, said Hong Kong people should know that
Hong Kong will become China's special administrative region after
handover. Thus, the concept of "One Country" is very important.
</P>
<P>
He said that the proposals have retained the basic principle of
guaranteeing Hong Kong people's freedom of speech as well as that
of association, assembly, procession and demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Yeung Yiu Chung, president of the Hong Kong Federation of
Education Workers, said that his federation agreed to adopting
restrictive measures on procession and demonstration.
</P>
<P>
He said that the organizers of assembly, procession and
demonstration should take into account the overall interests of
the local communities.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is natural and necessary for propose a ban on
donations from overseas organizations to Hong Kong's political
associations in order to prevent overseas organizations from
manipulating local associations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
