<HEADLINE> HK Handover Ceremony Attracts High-ranking Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 28 (Xinhua) -- About 40 foreign ministers and
other high-ranking officials and senior representatives from more
than 30 international organizations will attend Hong Kong's power
handover ceremony, a Hong Kong government official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the press this afternoon, Stephen Lam,
director of the Hong Kong Government Handover Ceremony
Coordination Office, said that his office has already sent
invitation letters to the related foreign governments and
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the list for the invitation was decided on by the
two sides of the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group (JLG).
</P>
<P>
His office will also invite more than 3,000 figures living in
Hong Kong to attend the ceremony which is to be held at the
midnight of June 30.
</P>
<P>
He said that all these figures have made contributions to Hong
Kong's economic development and its return to her motherland.
</P>
<P>
He said that the handover ceremony is a historic event and all
Hong Kong people are looking forward to it.
</P>
<P>
His office will have 400 staff members to make arrangements for
every specific work about the ceremony, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the registration of media organizations, he said that 7,343
journalists from 605 media organizations have turned in their
applications forms for the coverage of the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
According to Lam, 78 Hong Kong-based media organizations will
send 2,691 reporters to cover the ceremony, topping the
registration list.
</P>
<P>
Japan is second with 1,112 journalists from 29 media units and
the United States is third with 969 journalists from 78 media
organizations, followed by Britain with 633 and China with 601.
</P>
<P>
Lam said that the largest number of media organizations is from
 Europe with 182 organizations registered for the coverage of the
handover ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
