<HEADLINE> Manila Seeks Diplomatic Solution in Abduction Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said here today that Manila will exert diplomatic efforts to
resolve the case of seven Filipinos reportedly abducted by
Malaysian navymen in Palawan, in the southern Philippines, on
April 15.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Renato de Villa, who attended a cabinet
meeting in the Presidential Palace later today, said Ramos wanted
the case to be solved "diplomatically."
</P>
<P>
The President had formed a three-man committee to look into the
abduction of the fishermen, including a 10-year old boy, allegedly
by elements of the Malaysian Navy, de Villa said.
</P>
<P>
Members of the committee are de Villa, Foreign Secretary
Domingo Siazon and Interior and Local Governments Secretary Robert
Barbers.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened after a robbery, reportedly staged by
Filipino pirates, on a Malaysian island near Palawan on April 14,
said de Villa.
</P>
<P>
The next day, a naval patrol boat, resembling one of the
Malaysian Navy, entered Philippine territorial waters and anchored
off an islet in Palawan, about 60 kilometers from the Malaysian
state of Sabah.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian armed men seized seven fishermen and took them to
Malaysia. However, the police in Palawan said the Malaysians
seized the wrong people.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines Department of Foreign Affairs has mobilized its
entire staff in the Kuala Lumpur embassy, including Ambassador
Jose Brillantes, to ascertain the whereabouts of the seven
Filipinos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
