<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM to Start African Tour Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa will start an African tour Tuesday including Djibouti,
Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda to boost bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
"The tour comes within the framework of boosting cooperation
and friendship between Egypt and African countries and opening new
vistas of investment," Moussa told the Egyptian MENA news agency
today.
</P>
<P>
A number of joint projects will be inaugurated during the tour,
said the top Egyptian diplomat who will be accompanied by senior
officials of agriculture, irrigation and economy ministries in his
trip.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has put its expertise at the disposal of Tanzania, Kenya
and Uganda as regards the issue of using Nile river water, said
Egyptian Ambassador to Tanzania Mohamed Rafik Khalil in an
interview with Egyptian Voice of Arab radio.
</P>
<P>
Moussa will also be accompanied during his African tour by a
group of Egyptian businessmen capable of contributing to joint
investment projects between Egypt and each of these African
states, the ambassador added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda and six other Nile basin
countries share the river for drinking water.
</P>
<P>
Moussa will bring messages from President Hosni Mubarak to
President Hassan Gouled Aptidon of Djibouti, President Benjamin
Mkapa of Tanzania and President Daniel Arap Moi of Kenya, on joint
cooperation and exchange of views on issues of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Uganda, the last stop of his tour, Moussa
will complete the talks that started in Cairo during the Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni's two-day visit to Egypt last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Moussa will also have political consultation on the latest
developments in the Great Lake region.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has denied any military presence in any of the Great Lake
countries of Africa, that have been plagued by years of ethnic war
and flood of refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
