<HEADLINE> First Group of PMF Starts Mission in N. Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The first group of a projected
Peace Monitoring Force (PMF) has began its mission in northern
Iraq in a bid to supervise the truce between the two rival Kurdish
parties in the region.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported today that
the group of about 50 Iraqi Turkmens were deployed in the region
last week.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted sources here who declined to be named as saying
that the deployment of all the 180 Iraqi Turkmens and 20 Assyrians
is expected to be completed within the following few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Turkmens, who are part of the force, were trained in
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) and Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) agreed to the establishment of the PMF in last
February in the third round of the peace talks held in Ankara
co-sponsored by the United States, Britain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In last January, representatives from Turkey, the U.S. and
Britain met with Iraq' three delegations: the KDP, the PUK and
the Turkmen Front, to review progress in implementing the
principles agreed on October 31 and November 15 last year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is expected to provide the technical equipment of
the force and Turkey, backing Iraq's Turkmen minority because of
ethnic and cultural bonds, has persuaded the Kurds to offer
them a say in the administration of the area.
</P>
<P>
The KDP, supported by Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, fought
against the Iran-backed PUK in late August last year, which led to
U.S. air strikes against Iraqi military targets.
</P>
<P>
The two groups signed a peace deal on October 31, 1996, under
mediation of the U.S., Britain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The northern part of Iraq has been occupied by Kurdish rivals
since the Gulf War in 1991, but it split into rival zones after
the KDP and the PUK began fighting each other in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
