<HEADLINE> Philippines Sure of Peaceful End to Fishermen Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary
Renato de Villa said today he was confident of a peaceful solution
to the reported abduction of seven Filipino fishermen by Malaysian
navymen.
</P>
<P>
"Since we have very good and friendly relations with the
Malaysians, I believe diplomacy between the two countries will
handle the situation smoothly," De Villa said in an interview with
the local media.
</P>
<P>
De Villa was confident existing mechanisms for working out such
incidents -- the joint Philippine-Malaysian Committee and the
joint Philippine-Malaysian Border Operations Memorandum -- could
handle this case.
</P>
<P>
Seven Filipino fishermen, including a 10-year-old boy, were
detained by a group of Malaysian navymen on Mangsee Island, in
Balabac, on April 15, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
But the Malaysian police insisted the seven Filipinos were
arrested after they illegally entered Malaysian territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
