<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HABITAT Meeting Opens Amid Calls for Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The 58-member U.N. Commission on
Human Settlements opened its 16th session today with mounting
calls for having its role strengthened in a bid to improve the
human living conditions on earth.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to focus on how to revitalize the
organization to ensure effective implementation of the Habitat
Agenda and whether to expand the commission's membership to
include non-governmental groups.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. Center for Human Settlements (UNCHS) has played a
crucial role as the global focal point in advising and assisting
countries to formulate and implement shelter and human
settlements policies," said Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi-based UNCHS, governed by the commission, was
officially set up in 1978 with a goal to support governments in
the formulation of policies and strategies for developing
self-reliant management capacities.
</P>
<P>
"It has played an important role in preparing for the just
concluded HABITAT Two conference" where the Habitat Agenda, the
Global Plan of Action was adopted in Istanbul, Turkey, in 1996,
Moi said at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Istanbul conference has given the UNCHS a central role in
supporting the implementation of the Habitat Agenda, and in
policy guidance and coordination, said Wally N'dow, the Assistant
Secretary-General of Habitat.
</P>
<P>
"It called for the Commission's mandate to be reviewed and
strengthened," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which will end on May 7, is also to discuss the
issues of sustainable settlements development and of adequate
shelter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
