<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Malaysia to Discuss Dispute over Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and Malaysia today
started preparing the draft for special agreement on the dispute
over Sipadan and Ligitan islands, which will be jointly brought to
the International Court of Justice (ICJ) in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from the two countries opened their meeting on the
issue in Bandung, West Java, Indonesia, according to reports
reaching here this evening.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to finish the draft agreement during this meeting. But
that depends on the results of the discussions of course," said
Izhar Ibrahim, the Foreign Ministry's director general for
political affairs, who heads the Indonesian delegation.
</P>
<P>
The last meeting of the two delegations was held in Kuala
Lumpur in January this year.
</P>
<P>
The two tiny islands of Sipadan and Ligitan are located
northern of Kalimantan island of Indonesia. The dispute is a
legacy of the two countries' former colonial rules, the Dutch in
Indonesia and the British in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
According to a pact signed by Britain and the Netherlands in
1891, the two small islands are part of the territory of what was
then the Netherlands' East Indies, the present state of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Since then, maps of the Indonesian archipelago have
incorporated those two islands.
</P>
<P>
However, in 1969, Malaysia put the two islands on its national
maps as part of the country's territory. In 1983, Malaysia started
enforcing its claim over the islands with the passing of a state
law.
</P>
<P>
After the two sides failed to reach a bilateral agreement,
Indonesian President Soeharto and Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad agreed in October last year to bring the dispute
to the ICJ.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders pledged to abide by whatever decision the court
will hand down.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
