<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Automobile Exports Increase in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Japan exported about 3.85 million
automobiles between April 1996 and March 1997, an increase of 6.2
percent over the previous year, the Japanese Automobile Industry
Association said today.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time its exports have exceeded the previous
year after five years of continued shrinking. Since the
devaluation of the Japanese yen in the second half of last year,
Japan's automobile exports have increased, mainly to the the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Japanese cars occupied over 30 percent of the American market
in 1996, reaching the highest level yet.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Japan's automobile exports to the American and
European markets increased 5.3 percent and 5.8 percent
respectively over the previous year. However, its exports to
Asian markets reduced four percent because local Japanese
enterprises expanded their production in this area.
</P>
<P>
Exports in 1997 will maintain last year's momentum, since the
markets in the Middle and Near East as well as Latin America look
favorable, the Association said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
