<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Evidence Emerges for China's Invention of Printing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scholars set forth new
evidence on China's invention of printing at an ungoing exhibition
here today.
</P>
<P>
Sun Ji, a research fellow with the National Museum of Chinese
History, said that block printing, the earliest kind of printing,
was invented in China in the early Tang Dynasty (618-907) on the
basis of the use of seals, rubbing techniques, and printing on
fabrics.
</P>
<P>
"Before 751," Sun said, "China had already copied the Buddhist
Dharani Sutra by block printing. A copy of it was stored by Silla,
one of three ancient kingdoms on the Korean Peninsula, in a pagoda
in the Foguo (Buddhist World) Temple, which was built with Tang
help.
</P>
<P>
"The copy, found in October 1966, was the earliest copy of
Tang block printing ever found," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
According to Pan Jixing, a research fellow at the Institute of
Natural Sciences under the Chinese Academy of Sciences, the sutra
was translated during the reign of Emperor Wu Zetian (690-704) by
two monks, named Mitra Sanda and Fa Zang, from a copy written in
Sanskrit, at the empress' edict.
</P>
<P>
The copy was fetched from India by another monk, Yi Jing.
</P>
<P>
Historical records have shown that Empress Wu Zetian was very
pleased at seeing the translation and gave a big reward to the
translators, making it possible for the rapid copying of the
translation by block printing.
</P>
<P>
The printing was finished before 704, Pan said.
</P>
<P>
During the period a monk from Silla arrived in China, took
back a copy of the translated sutra and stored it in the pagoda,
according to Pan.
</P>
<P>
"Four characters created by Wu Zetian can be found in the
copy," Pan said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese experts also noted that the variations in Chinese
characters found in the copy are similar to those found in a
handwritten copy of the sutra, which was discovered in a cave in
the Mogao Grottoes in northwest China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
A duplicate of the copy found in Silla, the Mogao copy and a
duplicate of a Tang copy of the same sutra from the year 770 which
is now stored in Japan are on display at the exhibition at the
National Museum of Chinese History in the Tiananmen Square here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Evidence Emerges for China's Invention of Printing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As another proof of China's invention of printing in the early
Tang Dynasty, Sun mentioned a copy of the Diamond Sutra which was
made in 868.
</P>
<P>
The copy, found in the Mogao Grottoes and taken to Britain by
Aurel Stein early in this century, was regarded as the finest
example of Tang printing. On display at the exhibition is a
duplicate copy.
</P>
<P>
With a length of 488 cm and width of 30.5 cm, the copy has a
picture at the beginning, in which Sakyamuni is sitting
cross-legged on a lotus giving a lecture to his disciples, over
whom are flying female deva and banners.
</P>
<P>
"The lines of the picture were finely and exquisitely printed
and the characters are in the styles of famous calligraphers,
suggesting an achievement after a long period of development in
block printing," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
According to Sun, block printing was further developed in the
Song Dynasty (960-1279) before red and black block printing was
invented in the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368), on the basis of which
block printing using a wide range of colors was created in the
Ming Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
As the exhibition shows, letterboard printing was also invented
in China by Bi Sheng of the Northern Song Dynasty (960-1127), some
400 years earlier than Gutenberg's first printing work in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The most eye-catching letterboard printing at the exhibition is
a copy of a book printed using bronze letters in 1726, or the
fourth year under the Rein of Emperor Yong Zheng in Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911). The original book, titled "The Integration of Ancient
and Modern Books", was in 10,000 volumes with 160 million
characters, making it the largest encyclopedia in the world at the
time.
</P>
<P>
"China has contributed to world civilization by spreading
printing technology to both the east and the west in the past
centuries," Sun said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0081 </DOCNO>
