<HEADLINE> Singapore Court Strikes Out Lee Kuan Yew's Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The High Court of Singapore has
ordered that the remarks made by Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew on
Johor, a Southern state of Malaysia, be deleted from a court
document, local television reported today.
</P>
<P>
The television report said Justice Lai Kew Chai said that the
powers of the court must be used to maintain friendly relations
between Singapore and every other country.
</P>
<P>
The order was issued at the request of Lee Kuan Yew who made a
court appearance. Speaking for one-and-a-half hours, Lee said he
was carrying out an obligation he made to the Malaysian
government, the report said.
</P>
<P>
He reportedly said that the application to remove the remarks
was made in the interests of maintaining friendly relations
between Malaysia and Singapore. He added that he held the views
about Johor to be correct based on press reports.
</P>
<P>
He now accepts that the reports in the press have been disputed
and challenged, the television report said.
</P>
<P>
According to local media reports, Lee made controversial
remarks early this year in the affidavit filed in a Singapore
court hearing on defamation cases brought against opposition
Workers' Party member Tang Liang Hong by ruling People's Action
Party leaders.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Tang fled to Johor because he was concerned for his
safety, Lee Kuan Yew said: "I was baffled. He claimed his life was
under threat. But, of all places, he went to Johor. That place is
notorious for shootings, muggings and car-jackings. It does not
make sense for a person who claims to be fearful for his life to
go to a place like Johor."
</P>
<P>
Lee Kuan Yew apologized "unreservedly" twice in March to
Malaysia for the offense he has caused to the government and
people of Malaysia by his statement on Johor and made it clear
that he "had no intention to cause offense" in his sworn affidavit
made on January 27 this year.
</P>
<P>
Then the senior minister instructed his counsel to seek the
court's permission to have the offending sentences deleted.
</P>
</TEXT>
