<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Pak Struggles to Educate Rural Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- At first glance, I thought the
small and low thatched shack adjoining a single-story house was a
shelter set up by an Afghan refuge family who like thousands of
others came across the border into northwestern Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
When I went nearer, I was surprised to find it was a
"classroom" where about 20 children sitting on the ground were
reading their textbooks following a bearded slim young man.
</P>
<P>
It can hardly be called a classroom because there were no basic
facilities in the ten-square-meter space except a small blackboard
propped up with two stools.
</P>
<P>
This is a village near Batkhela, about 300 kilometers northwest
of Islamabad, in the Malakand Agency of the North West Frontier
Province (NWFP).
</P>
<P>
"It is the sole free-of-charge primary school set up mainly for
the poor farmers' children in the village," said 26-year-old Ahmad
Ali, who suspended his class to have a chat with me.
</P>
<P>
Ali's school was one of the non-formal basic education schools,
part of the effort made by the present government led by Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif to improve education for the children
especially in the rural area.
</P>
<P>
The Nawaz government, while giving priority to national
economic revival, has also been preparing a comprehensive plan for
the improvement of primary education, particularly in rural areas,
where 60 percent of the country's population inhabit.
</P>
<P>
The non-formal basic education system is based on the home
school idea without any formal building and local community
provides free-of-charge room in the area. And learning times in
these non-formal schools are not rigid and adjustable.
</P>
<P>
Ali, who is paid only about 2,000 rupees (50 U.S. dollars), is
teaching a total of 42 teenagers, who were divided into three
grades and were taught with different textbooks at different times
in the day.
</P>
<P>
"I volunteered as their teacher because I feel it so important
yet so difficult for these rural children to get access to
education," said Ali, who usually comes to his school by bike from
his village, about six kilometers from Batkhela.
</P>
<P>
Ali, who is single, said these children's parents, whose income
mainly depends on limited field yields, could hardly send their
children to the formal schools in faraway big cities.
</P>
<P>
"Our country could not achieve the target of progress and
prosperity without the improvement in the literacy rate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ali's view was echoed by many education experts in Pakistan,
where the official literacy rate is 37 percent, one of the lowest
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Education is perhaps the prime area where the greatest emphasis
must be placed if Pakistan is to attain sustainability of the
economic and social development, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to available statistics, by the end of this century,
with an estimated population growth of 3 percent, Pakistan, with a
population of 130 million now, will face an alarming situation of
over 100 million illiterate people.
</P>
<P>
"I hope more and more non-informal schools will be established
and more and more people will involve in this project, which gives
the rural children an opportunity to change their lot," Ali said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
