<HEADLINE> Population Explosion, Threat to Economy: Pak Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Minister for
Population Welfare Syeda Abida Hussain described here today the
population explosion as a threat to the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The high-rising population growth rate must be controlled for
the socio-economic development in Pakistan, which has a population
of about 130 million and its growth rate is about 3 percent, Abida
said when inaugurating a meeting on women's studies.
</P>
<P>
Abida warned that if proper measures were not taken to check
the baby boom, the population would increase manifold.
</P>
<P>
She maintained that overpopulation was the main hurdle in the
way of socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
The government was keen to check population growth by promoting
family planning programs, she said.
</P>
<P>
The government also wanted to elevate the status of women by
providing them maximum opportunities in all fields of life, she
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister called for creating awareness about the
consequences of overpopulation and its negative effects on the
national economy.  
