<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore-ESCAP Third Country Training Accord Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Singapore and the Economic and
Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) signed a
Memorandum of Understanding in Bangkok today to establish a Third
Country Training Program (TCTP) for ESCAP developing countries in
the region, the Singapore Foreign Ministry said here today.
</P>
<P>
It said that Singapore is the first country to sign such an
agreement with the ESCAP to jointly conduct training courses for
the ESCAP developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"This is a reflection of the general growing support for
Singapore's technical assistance approach which focuses on human
resource development as a vital catalyst for economic
development," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
To date, Singapore has joint training program with eight
partner countries, namely Japan, Germany, United Kingdom, Republic
of Korea, Australia, Canada, Norway and Luxembourg. Singapore also
cooperate with international organizations to provide training
programs for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The training program with the ESCAP, jointly administered by
the Technical Cooperation Directorate of the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs of Singapore, and the ESCAP, will enable Singapore to
enhance its technical assistance program to developing countries
in Asia and the Pacific region, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed today, two courses will be conducted
this year and the first is a course in "Tourism Management" which
is scheduled from May 26 to 31. It is tailored for the South
Pacific island countries. Future courses would cover other fields
like trade promotion, port management and project planning.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1947 in Shanghai, China, the ESCAP was first
known as the Economic Commission for Asia and the Far East (ECAFE)
to assist in post-war economic reconstruction. The Commission
subsequently moved its headquarters to Bangkok in January 1949
where it adopted its present name to reflect both the economic and
social aspects of development and the geographic location of its
members countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
