<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sees Dull Productive Sector in 1st </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Productivity lulled in Nigeria's
real sector in the first quarter of this year, dulling the
feasibility of 5.5 percent gross domestic product growth
projected in the budget.
</P>
<P>
The poor performance in the productive sector was attributed
by industry operators and financial analysts here to the
inability of the government to initiate some basic projects and
policies promised in the budget.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's head of state General Sani Abacha announced earlier
that policies in the year's budget were targeted at raising the
level of productive activities in particular.
</P>
<P>
But the policies such as privatization of some public agencies
have not yet been implemented, industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
The government's retention of dual exchange rate and pursuit
of a surplus budget were also factors leading to the poor
situation.
</P>
<P>
According to some analysts, the impact of agriculture which is
an integral part of the real sector was not felt in the economy
largely because of its seasonal nature in the country.
</P>
<P>
Capacity utilization in the manufacturing sector was too low
as many manufacturers avoided fresh production owing to huge
stocks of unsold finished goods in their warehouses, they said,
adding that this stagnated the economy.
</P>
<P>
The long-drawn fuel crisis nationwide recently was also cited
as a factor that hampered productivity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At Least 4 Killed in Renewed Fighting in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 28 (Xinhua) -- At least four people have been
killed and seven others wounded in a renewed fighting between the
militiamen of faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid and those of
his rival, Osman Ali Atto in Mogadishu, sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The heavy armed clashes occurred last night in the generally
dark Somali capital which was lit by the night flares used by the
opposing sides around the fighting zones.
</P>
<P>
During the fighting which lasted about 90 minutes, no
territorial gains was made by either side, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the renewed fighting is not yet known. However,
Osman Ali Atto's faction has made their usual accusation of
blaming Hussein Mohamed Aidid's men for provoking their front
line forces.
</P>
<P>
There's no official word from the faction led by Hussein
Mohamed Aidid over the fighting as yet, but a militia officer
loyal to his faction has denied that their forces have made the
attack.
</P>
<P>
This fighting between the two clan compatriots was taking
place at a time when international efforts are continuing towards
a political reconciliation for the Somali factions.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the fighting, the faction leaders of Osman Ali Atto
and Hussein Mohamed Aidid are currently being hosted by President
Ali Abdalle Saleh of Yemen.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that a meeting between Hussein Aidid and Osman
Atto will take place tomorrow in the capital of Yemen, Sana.
</P>
</TEXT>
