<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto in Australia to Push Strategic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto said here today, "Further promotion of bilateral
relations among Japan, the United States, China and Australia will
contribute greatly to the peace and prosperity of the Asia-Pacific
region."
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that there can be, and should be positive
relations among these four relationships," Hashimoto declared in
his speech at a dinner hosted by Prime Minister John Howard
tonight.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto arrived here this afternoon with a 60-member
entourage to a full state welcome. His two-day visit is aimed at
broadening the strategic partnership between Japan and Australia.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese leader proposed a series of measures to strengthen
bilateral relations, which included an annual summit between the
two prime ministers and a partnership agenda to broaden
cooperation on issues such as energy, the environment, education,
culture, science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also pledged Japan's support for Australia to join
the Asia-Europe Meeting. In return, it was believed that Japan
would ask Australia to support Japan's bid for a permanent seat in
the United Nations security Council.
</P>
<P>
The visit marks the 40th anniversary of the two countries'
trade agreement which laid the foundation of what is now
Australia's most important economic relationship.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed that in 1995-96, the two-way trade
reached 27.2 billion Australian dollars (21.2 billion U.S.
dollars), five billion Australian dollars (3.9 billion U.S.
dollars) more than that between Australian and the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
