<HEADLINE> S'pore Port Authority Signs Contract For 2nd Port Venture in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Port of Singapore Authority
(PSA) signed a contract with the Fuzhou Port Authority (FPA) to
form joint venture companies to manage and operate the existing
container terminals at Qingzhou and Daijiang, in east China's
Fujian province, the PSA announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, which was signed last Friday, the joint
venture companies formed would also develop and manage a new
deep-water container terminal outside Minjiang. This would be the
PSA's second port venture in China, it said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the PSA will invest in this project through its
wholly-owned subsidiary, Sealion Huanan Pte Ltd., with two Hong
Kong-based joint venture partners, Ranki Development Ltd. and
Pacific Industries and Development Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou's container volume enjoyed a robust growth of 30,500
twenty-foot equivalent units (TEUs) in 1990 to 177,000 TEUs in
1996. It has also been designated recently as one of the two ports
open for direct shipping links between Chinese mainland and
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The PSA noted that with increasing Taiwanese investments in
Fuzhou and growing trade between the two sides across the Taiwan
Straits, Fuzhou is poised to become an important gateway for
direct shipping links between the two sides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
