<HEADLINE> Guizhou Opens Wider to Outside World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Guizhou, a resource-rich but
underdeveloped region in southwest China, will host a series of
business and trade activities in late May to accelerate economic
reform and opening-up to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Wang Siqi, vice governor of Guizhou said in Beijing today that
the province will take advantage of the opening of a new modern
airport in Guiyang, the provincial capital, on May 28, to invite
overseas investors and visitors to a large trade fair and an
international symposium on Guizhou's economic reform and
development.
</P>
<P>
The new airport in Guiyang, which cost 1.3 billion yuan (156.6
million US dollars) to build, is seen as a breakthrough for this
inland region's civil aviation industry. A ceremony will be held
at the opening of the new facility.
</P>
<P>
The investment and trade fair, scheduled between May 28 and
June 1, will offer 235 standard booths and 1,084 projects for both
domestic and overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The 97 Guizhou International Symposium on Reform and
Development will be jointly held by the Guizhou Provincial
Government and the State Commission for Restructuring the Economy
(SCRE) between May 26 and 27. It will be a high-level
international academic meeting, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
"SCRE is very much concerned about the economic development in
China's central and west regions, as these regions are facing rare
opportunities", said Guo Shuqing, a well-known economist and
Secretary-General of SCRE.
</P>
<P>
The symposium is designed to probe ways of narrowing the gaps
between the coastal regions in the east and the inland region in
the west, and help Guizhou in its economic and social
developments, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The province will also promote several new tourist routes
during the late May and early June activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
