<HEADLINE> Manila Increases Navy Patrol Near Malaysia Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine military recently
deployed additional navy boats to patrol the area near the common
border of the Philippines and Malaysia, a senior military official
said today.
</P>
<P>
Reynaldo Reyes, Western Command Chief of the Armed Forces of
the Philippines, said three more navy boats were deployed this
week to patrol the Philippine territorial waters near its common
border with Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The development came on the heels of the detention of seven
Philippine fishermen by the Malaysian authorities.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said he was informed by residents of a fishing village
that Malaysians rounded up six Filipino fishermen and a
10-year-old boy on April 15.
</P>
<P>
But Malaysian police said the seven Filipinos were arrested for
illegal entry into Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said he requested the Malaysian official to help release
the detained Filipinos on the grounds that there are "conflicting
versions" about the manner and reason for their detention.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Fidel Ramos has ordered Foreign Affair
Secretary Domingo Siazon, Defense Secretary Renato de Villa and
Interior and Local Governments Secretary Robert Barbers to look into
the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
