<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Explosion in Russian Military Depot Still On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The explosion of a military depot
in the far east region of Russia halted dozens of trains on the
Trans-Siberian railway, the Interfax news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The explosion, which erupted Sunday afternoon, continued for
nearly a whole day and made rescue virtually impossible. Splinters
from exploding artillery shells were strewn around a radius of 12
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The traffic on the Trans-Siberian railway, which passes near
the depot, was interrupted, with 25 passenger and 60 freight trains
halted.
</P>
<P>
The blast also posed a grave threat to the safety of the
residents in the town of Bira, six kilometers southeast of the
depot.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the people in Bira have been evacuated, but
about 2,000 residents refused to leave and stayed in their homes,
a spokesman for the Russian Ministry for Emergency Situations
said. So far, there is no report of casualties.
</P>
<P>
Over 400 emergency workers have been sent to the area to contain
the explosion, which is believed by local officials to be sparked
by a forest fire Sunday. But experts did not rule out the
possibility of sabotage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
