<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earliest Cultivated Rice Found in 8,000-year-old Tribal Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
found the world's earliest cultivated rice at an 8,000-year-old
tribal site by the Dongting Lake in central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Previously the origin of rice culture was traced to India in
about 3000 BC.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 rice kernels of different sizes have been
found at the site, which is believed to be the oldest tribal
remains along the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the rice, some of which were more than four
times the size of others, may be an intermediate type between wild
rice and cultivated one.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists also unearthed 47 kinds of plant seeds and a
great number of animal bones, materials by which the
archaeologists will research human's agricultural production and
settled life between the old and new Stone Age periods.
</P>
<P>
The site, more than 120 meters long and 110 meters wide, was
surrounded by a moat and a wall, in which dwelling remains, and
over 50 tombs were found.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 pieces of pottery, wooden ware, bone ware, hemp
ropes, reed mats, and baskets have been unearthed from the tombs
after archaeologists' five-year work.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists believe that some wooden and bone wares were used
as agricultural production tools, including a 90-cm-long wooden
tool to dig earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
