<HEADLINE> CPC Official Meets Japanese Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Li Tieying, member of the
Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC) Central
Committee, met here this afternoon with a delegation of the
Liberal Democratic Party of Japan led by Yamazaki Taku, chairman
of the party's Political Affairs Investigation Committee.
</P>
<P>
Extending a warm welcome to the Japanese visitors, Li, also
state councillor, said this year is the 25th anniversary of the
normalization of the diplomatic relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The development of Sino-Japanese friendly cooperative relations
is hard-won, Li said, adding that the Chinese government has
always considered it an important state policy to develop
long-term and steady relations of friendship with Japan.
</P>
<P>
Li hoped the Liberal Democratic Party, as the ruling party of
Japan, plays an even more active role in promoting the healthy and
steady progress of the China-Japan ties.
</P>
<P>
Yamazaki Taku noted his current visit is aimed to study the
Japan-China relations oriented towards the 21st century through
the exchanges of the two parties.
</P>
<P>
The Liberal Democratic Party of Japan is willing to strengthen
contacts and exchanges with the CPC in an effort to contribute to
the advancement of the relations between the two neighboring
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese visitors, as the CPC guests, arrived here this
afternoon. Soon after, Yamazaki Taku held working talks with Li
Shuzheng, head of the International Department of the CPC Central
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The CPC and the Liberal Democratic Party started to forge
relations of friendly exchanges in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
