<HEADLINE> Jordan Welcomes Efforts to Hold Four-Nation Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Jordan said today that it welcomes
any efforts to hold a summit, including Jordan, Egypt, the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and Israel, which is inteded
to bring the peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
This came in remarks by Jordanian Minister of State for Media
Affairs, Samir Mutawe in an exclusive interview published by the
Jordanian newspaper "Al-Dustour" today.
</P>
<P>
Mutawe said that the Jordanian leadership welcomes any joint
Arab effort intended to bring the Middle East peace process back
on its proper track, but he said that the Egyptian proposal for
holding a four-nation summit has not yet been offered to Jordan's
political leadership.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak last Friday suggested
holding such a summit to include King Hussein of Jordan,
Mubarak himself, the PNA President Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, in collaboration with the United
States, a co-sponsor of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The holding of such a summit is reported to depend on how far
Israel is willing to reconsider its settlement policy in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian minister of state pointed out that any contacts
about the proposed summit should be made through diplomatic
channels or political envoys. 
</P>
</TEXT>
