<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Minister Alain Juppe Sunday revealed the
primary measures that the ruling majority would take if it wins
the legislative elections. The measures, surprisingly similar with
the proposals of the opposition Socialist Party, include the
reduction of working hours and restriction of the number of terms
to be served by parliamentary deputies and government ministers.
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli newspaper Yediot Aharonot published last weekend
an interview it made 20 years ago with former Israeli Defense
Minister Moshe Dayan but was censored by Israeli
authorities. Dayan said that he made a big error by allowing
Israeli troops occupy the Golan Heights in June 1967, because
Syria did not pose a threat to Israel at that time.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro
</P>
<P>
-- According to a new poll by Le Figaro and Sofres polling
institute, the French ruling majority will maintain 329 seats in
the 577-seat legislature after the general elections. However, 36
percent of the people polled said that they are undecided yet whom
will vote for.
</P>
<P>
-- Togolese President Gnassingbe Eyadema has called for the
rapid establishment of a Pan-African peace-keeping force to
prevent the war in Zaire from spreading to neighboring
countries. He said that "the risks of contagion" from the war in
Zaire are real, because of the rampant trans-frontier trafficking
of weapons in African countries. 
</P>
