<HEADLINE> Beijing to Give Priority to Public Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Beijing plans to take the
national lead in giving priority to developing public means of
transport and solving urban traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
The special bus lane on Chang'an Avenue, Beijing's busiest
downtown artery five kilometers long, will open before June 30.
</P>
<P>
Another three bus lanes have been scheduled for Chongwenmenwai,
Fuchengmenwai, and Chaoyangmennei streets within this year,
according to Chen Zemin, director of the municipal Urban Traffic
Administration.
</P>
<P>
"This is a consideration for the masses," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that Beijing's road conditions cannot meet the demand
of the increasing number of motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of motor vehicles rose by
150,000 in 1995, and increased another 140,000 in 1996. In the
first quarter of this year, the figure still climbed 42,000,
bringing the city's total to 1.16 million.
</P>
<P>
Too many vehicles causes traffic chaos. Driving against traffic
regulations is still commonly seen, and management at road
crossings is difficult, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has decided to increase patrol policemen on roads, and
set up TV monitoring systems over the second- and third-ring roads
in the city, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
And long-arm signal lamps, which can stretch to the middle part
of streets and be easily seen by drivers, will be soon set up at
11 crossings in Chang'an Avenue, he added.
</P>
<P>
The city will also add more parks for cars by June, according
to Chen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
