<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Direct Elections of Village Committees Conducted Across China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The provinces of Fujian,
Heilongjiang, Shanxi, and Hebei are holding direct elections of
village officials as part of China's experiment in grass-roots
democracy and marking another step forward, according to a
Ministry of Civil Affairs official.
</P>
<P>
From 1988 to early 1997, 18 Chinese provincial administrative
areas held three direct elections of village heads. Coastal Fujian
Province in eastern China, and Heilongjiang Province in
northeastern China are now holding their fourth round since 1988.
</P>
<P>
"The direct election of village committees in the vast
countryside is a major grass-roots political reform," according to
Wang Zhenyao, a senior official with the Ministry of Civil Affairs
who is in charge of developing grass-roots political power.
</P>
<P>
In the early '80s, economic restructuring in the countryside
resulted in profound changes in rural economic and social
relations, and provided a stronger foundation for the direct
election of village officials, Wang explained.
</P>
<P>
Then, in November 1987, the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, China's top legislature, adopted a trial law,
the Organization of Village Committees Law, which calls for
village officials be chosen by villagers.
</P>
<P>
The law took effect on June 1, 1988. The move was viewed by
many to have marked the beginning of village autonomy. Says Wang,
"The direct grass-roots election is a major policy to get a system
of democratic autonomy to take root in the daily life of
villagers, and it is an extremely large and complicated project."
</P>
<P>
He notes that the process is different in different places.
With the establishment of village committees across the country in
1984, the cities of Beijing and Tianjin, the provinces of Hebei
and Heilongjiang, and the autonomous regions of Inner Mongolia,
Tibet and Xinjiang began to enact local regulations on the
election of village committees. But, they were still in the
planning stage before 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Direct Elections of Village Committees Conducted Across China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As soon as the Organization of Village Committees Law took
effect in 1988, many provincial governments developed local rules
to implement the law.
</P>
<P>
That year, 1,093 counties did pilot work for electing village
heads, increasing people's awareness of the law and of democratic
elections, establishing a village conference system, working out
regulations on managing village affairs, and training village
officials.
</P>
<P>
From the last half of 1988 to early 1989, direct elections of
village committees were held in 14 provinces, municipalities, and
autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, more than 20 counties experimented with choosing the
director of the village committee from several candidates.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, the central government urged local governments to
push for elections of village committees and for village autonomy.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1992, many villages across the country had held
at least one election of village committees, and provincial
legislatures in Fujian, Hebei, and Heilongjiang provinces had
worked out regulations on implementing the national law.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Fujian improved its election methods and organized its
third set of village election since 1988.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 and 1996, villagers in 24 provinces, municipalities,
and autonomous regions elected new village officials and the
election standards had improved a great deal because provincial
governments were responsible for helping design election
procedures and times, and for training election workers.
</P>
<P>
In the process, farmers have become motivated and know better
how to safeguard their own interests in accordance with the
law. More than 90 percent of rural voters have taken part in the
elections.
</P>
<P>
"The election of village committees has, as a matter of fact,
acted as a training class for both villagers and government
officials on how to develop rural grass-roots democracy," Wang
Zhenyao concluded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Industrial Projects Operate in Weifang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Weifang High Technology Industry
Development Zone has launched eight new industrial projects.
</P>
<P>
With a total investment of 23 million US dollars, the eight
projects are mostly overseas-funded. The largest part is a
fertilizer project, wholly-owned by a US company, and is expected
to yield 30 million US dollars in profits.
</P>
<P>
Located in east of Weifang, a middle-sized city in east China's
Shandong Province, Weifang High Technology Industry Development
Zone is one of the seven state-level exemplary bases to extend
scientific and technological achievements since it was founded in
1992.
</P>
<P>
Weifang High Technology Industry Development Zone has attracted
400 enterprises with overseas investment totalling 600 million US
dollars. The output value per capita of the Weifang development
zone ranks seventh among China's 52 state-level high technology
zones.  
</P>
</TEXT>
