<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian Grasslands Attract More Overseas Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Hulun Buir Grasslands in the
northern part of China have become a new tourism attraction and
have attracted more than 1.6 million overseas tourists over the
past five years because of the scenery and pollution-free
environment.
</P>
<P>
Hulun Buir covers 250,000 sq. km. or about six times the size
of switzerland, and has 80,000 sq. km. of China's most beautiful
grasslands, and the Great Hinggan Mountains with their primeval
forests and more than 3,000 rivers and 500 lakes.
</P>
<P>
The grasslands have more than 3,000 kinds of plants and over
400 kinds of animals, and 35 minority groups, including the Oroqen
people, one of China's smallest minority groups.
</P>
<P>
Tumur, a Mongolian photographer who has published a book of
photos of the Hulun Buir Grasslands, said that because they are
located on a border area, industrial development has not brought
pollution problems and their good ecology has been preserved.
</P>
<P>
He said that the unique scenery here has attracted more
tourists and that local tourism departments have developed a
number of programs that include grasslands tours, skiing in the
winter, hunting tours in snow covered forests, and tours of
minority areas and cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
He said that the local government places great importance on
tourism and finished the Hailar International Airport extension
project and opened air routes to Hohhot (the regional capital of
Inner Mongolia), Beijing, Dalian (a coastal city in Liaoning
Province), Harbin (the capital of Heilongjiang) and highways and
railways that go to major tourist spots in other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
There are 15 travel agencies with grasslands programs and seven
modern hotels there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
