<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Welfare to foucs on Aiding Orphans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China's social welfare efforts
will focus on improving conditions in the country's orphanages and
on helping Tibet develop more public welfare services in 1997, a
Civil Affairs Ministry official said today.
</P>
<P>
"Top priority in our social welfare for 1997 is first to
refurbish houses for children, and then to develop Tibet's social
welfare services," Xu Ruixin, vice-minister of Civil Affairs, told
a press conference.
</P>
<P>
China has 100,000 orphans, but only 84 orphanages and 700
welfare institutions that can care for them.
</P>
<P>
The ministry decided to choose 100 juvenile houses from 29
provinces and municipalities that most need reworking, to
refurbish living spaces, and to provide better medical and
rehabilitation equipment for them. A total of 250 million yuan
(30.12 million US dollars) has been collected for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Half of the projects have been completed and the rest will be
finished by the end of this year, he said, adding: "support for
Tibet's social welfare services is especially important for social
stability, ethnic unity, consolidation of frontiers, and the
anti-splittism struggle."
</P>
<P>
The ministry has pledged that it will collect 100 million yuan
to build housing for juveniles and other public institutions that
Tibet badly needs.
</P>
<P>
1997 has also being named "the year of assisting Tibet" by
civil affairs departments across the country.
</P>
<P>
Xu also discussed China's welfare lottery system. Since the
issue of the first welfare lottery in 1987 to the end of last
year, 19.43 billion yuan worth of tickets were sold, raising 6.09
billion yuan in funds.
</P>
<P>
Of that, 4.3 billion yuan has been spent on 62,922 projects,
according to the vice-minister. But, the country still needs 32
billion yuan for the 1996-2000 period for welfare institutions,
medical equipment, housing for orphans, and a national low-income
security system.
</P>
<P>
He called on the public to give more support to the country's
welfare lottery program for the "coordinated development of social
welfare with the national economy."  
</P>
</TEXT>
