<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, April 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The 26th Houston International Festival closed on
Sunday with Chinese culture honored in the Southern U.S. city. It
was the first time that the Houston International Festival was
held with a spotlight on Chinese culture since it started in
1972. More than 80 Chinese artists performed acrobatics and folk
arts, and played traditional Chinese music instruments.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The G-24 developing countries are considering a
certain sort of summit dialogue with the G-7 most industrial
countries, said Antonio Casas Gonzalez, Chairman of the
Intergovernmental Group of 24 on International Monetary
Affairs. Gonzalez, who made the announcement after concluding the
56th Ministerial meeting here on Sunday, said that a technical
group, which includes some G-24 and G-7 countries, will be set up
to study the possibility of the summit, but it is too early to
tell the concrete plan for such dialogue.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Zaire's rebel leader Laurent-Desire Kabila on Sunday
asked the United Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) to
repatriate within 60 days tens of thousands of Rwandan refugees
dying of hunger and disease in the region of Kisangani. Meanwhile,
he proposed to Zairian President Mobutu Sese Seko that they meet
in the Zambian capital Lusaka. UNHCR regional coordinator for
central Africa Filippo Grandi said although the "ultimatum" given
by Kabila is short, the UNHCR will try to repatriate the refugees.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- An 18-year-old Palestinian youth was shot dead by
Israeli soldiers in the West Bank on Sunday night. A report of
JMCC, a Palestinian press service based in East Jerusalem, said on
Monday that the incident took place in the Village of Tharaz near
Hebron when young Palestinian stone-throwers clashed with Israeli
troops. The boy, named Issam Aqadneh, was killed on the spot and
two other Palestinian youths were wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
