<HEADLINE> Top Commanders in N. Uganda Return to Their </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Top commanders of the government
troops in northern Uganda have returned to their headquarters in
Gulu, northern Uganda, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Major General Salim Saleh, presidential adviser on military
affairs in the north, Colonel James Kazini, commander of the
Fourth Division, and Lt. Colonel Nakibus Lakara, his deputy,
appeared in public in various occasions after weeks of absence.
</P>
<P>
The first reports on their movement northward reaching here on
April 20. Their shifting coincided with the Ugandan army's build
up in the north and intensified fighting between Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA) against the Sudanese government troops and
Lord's Resistance Army in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan army sealed the Uganda-Sudan border and roads
northward to Sudan and launched a series of operations against
LRA in the region.
</P>
<P>
The top army commanders returned to their base since Odur, one
of three top field commanders of LRA and his 70 subordinates have
been killed.
</P>
<P>
The LRA, a rebel group acting in northern Uganda with its
bases in southern Sudan, has three detachments. Odur commanded
one of them, according to "The Monitor" today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
