<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Initial Report on Philippine Hotel Fire Cites Arson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The initial official report on the
New Imperial Hotel fire in the southern Philippine city Cotabato,
which killed 27 people early Saturday morning, has pointed to
arson, Philippine News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The report was sent by the City Fire Marshall Inspector
Edzrapel Dilawangan to the regional office of the Bureau of Fire
Protection in Koronadal, South Cotabato, on Sunday, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
"Careful evaluation and analysis of the result of further
investigation conducted as of date disclosed that the nature of
fire is attributed to be sabotage-fire by still unidentified
persons with ill-motive," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report further stated that "the fire started at 'holy hour'
approximately 12:30 midnight" which was considered "as one of the
prima-facie evidences of arson."
</P>
<P>
The report also said the spread of fire is also questionable as
"burning was simultaneous" in the upper three floors of the
five-storey hotel, the portion totally gutted by fire.
</P>
<P>
But, the report said that unless evidences prove otherwise,
"the fire is presumed accidental in nature."
</P>
<P>
As of today, fire investigators have not discovered sufficient
evidences, such as gasoline containers or any other chemicals,
that could positively link the fire to arson, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Dilawangan, speaking over a local radio station, pointed out
that "evidences of arson are still very weak as of this time."
</P>
<P>
He requested authorities to give them more time to come up with
concrete evidences on the case.
</P>
<P>
The two-hour blaze started at a room on the third floor which
was reserved for use as a prayer room of the Muslim guests who
were there to attend Muslim Mindanao Governor Nur Misuari's
state-of-the-region address originally scheduled for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, the tragedy forced Misuari to call off his address.
</P>
</TEXT>
