<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Set Up Enforcement of Intellectual Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today said his government will pursue with "greater vigor" the
effective enforcement of laws on intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
Ramos made the remarks before the World Intellectual Property
Organization's World Symposium on Broadcasting, New Communication
Technologies and Intellectual Property here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said his government was restructuring intellectual
property rights laws to make them more responsive to the growing
economy.
</P>
<P>
He said he has created a presidential inter-agency committee on
intellectual property rights to coordinate the effective
enforcement of the intellectual property rights laws.
</P>
<P>
The president added that there were pending bills in Congress
seeking to strengthen the country's patent, trademark and
copyright laws.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that in the past the Philippines fell behind in
giving recognition to the part played by intellectual property in
nation-building owing to the negative perception that intellectual
property rights only protect the interests of more developed
economies.
</P>
<P>
But he said the country's failure to appreciate significance of
intellectual property will not happen anymore.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also said that the three-day symposium will help guide
the government in formulating the best approach in addressing the
issues on the conferment of property rights to broadcasting
organizations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
