<BODY>
<HEADLINE> b d k 1800 China-Inner Mongolia-Australia China, Australia Jointly Launch Pasture Protection Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China and Australia jointly
launched a pasture protection program today in Horqin Grasslands
in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The program, aiming at protecting the ecological resources of
the pastures and raising income of farmers and herdsmen in Horqin
Grasslands, is aided by the Australian Agency for International
Development (AUSAID) and the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
The program will absorb more than 70 million yuan (8.75 million
US dollars). Australia will offer 6.19 million Australian dollars
and the Chinese side will collect nearly 30 million yuan (3.7
million dollars) for the program.
</P>
<P>
Xu Baoyin, chief of Animal Husbandry Bureau of Hinggan League
(Ulan Hot City) and Chinese chief of the joint program, said the
program is the region's largest pasture improvement project in the
past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and Australian experts estimated that about 24,000
people from 5,700 farming or herding households are expected to
take part in the program.
</P>
<P>
After implementation of the program, the per unit grass output
could be raised by six times and the annual net income of
households participating in the program could rise from 7,600 yuan
(950 dollars) to nearly 12,000 yuan (1,500 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia is China's first region to build the system of
regional autonomy of minority nationalities and is also one of
major pastures in China with a grassland area of 8.8 million
hectares.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, China has been introducing foreign aid to
launch pasture improvement programs in the minority nationality
areas and so far more than 100 Sino-foreign pasture protection
programs have been launched.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
