<HEADLINE> Farmers in Shanxi Earn More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The per capita income of the
rural population in North China's Shanxi Province hit 1,557 yuan
in 1996, up nearly 29 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
This was seven percentage points above the national average and
the highest growth rate in the history of Shanxi, said a local
agricultural official.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the higher income to last year's good
grain harvest. As a structural readjustment took place in
agriculture, the grain output climbed to a new high, exceeding 10
billion kg.
</P>
<P>
In grain producing areas, 70 percent of the annual income comes
from farming.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Shouyang County produced an average of 1,000 kg of
grain last year, earning an extra 300 yuan a year each.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, forestry in Shanxi is flourishing. Forested areas
cover 13.5 million mu (900,450 hectares) and have added nearly 100
yuan to the income of rural residents in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Groundnut Production Rises in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The annual groundnut production
in Uganda in recent years stands at around 140,000 metric tons,
increasing by 6,000 tons from the estimated production in 1988,
reported the local daily "The New Vision" today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that after the introduction of new varieties
that are resistant to diseases, the country's groundnut
production will surely rise again.
</P>
<P>
However, Charles Busolo-Bulafu, a groundnut researcher at
Serere Research Station over 200 km northeast of Kampala, was
quoted as saying that incidentally, all the groundnut crop in the
country is grown by small scale peasant farmers who have limited
means.
</P>
<P>
Rosette virus disease and early leaf rot as well as bacterial
wilt, rust and stem rot cause considerable loss in yields. And
the farmers also have to battle with the pests which include
aphids, white grubs and termites, he added.
</P>
<P>
Groundnut growing introduced in Uganda in 1862 is presently
widely grown throughout the country. Apart from being highly
nutritious, groundnuts are an important raw material for the oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
With an oil content of up to 56 percent, groundnuts have the
highest oil content among the oil seed crops in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Groundnut, a multipurpose crop is also the second most widely
grown grain legume in the country after beans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Grain Aid Project in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Construction on a project aided by
the World Food Programme (WFP) and International Fund on
Agriculture Development (IFAD) recently started in northwest
China's Qinghai province.
</P>
<P>
The "5717" project, the largest grain aid project in Qinghai,
involves a total of 17.87 million US dollars, 12.65 million of
that coming free from the WFP, and 52.22 million US dollars in
loans from the IFAD. The Chinese government will put in an equal
amount of funds.
</P>
<P>
The project will cover 522 villages in 34 townships in three
counties for building new agriculture infrastructure, improving
the environment, and increasing peasants' incomes with water
conservation projects, terracing fields, and repairing roads.
</P>
<P>
The project will also provide technological training for 84,000
women and will help 20,000 women learn to read and 2,000 female
dropouts return to school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
