<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawian Government Loses 26 Million Dollars From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Malawian government suffered
a loss of 26 million US Dollars in the past year in the civil
service from fraudulent accounting, overpayment and ghost
workers, said a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Malawian Finance Minister Aleke Banda
based on a government investigation while presenting the 1997/98
budget to Parliament last week, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Banda said that irregularities included retention of retired
employees on payroll, deliberate fraudulent acts such as payments
to employees who had died, retired, dismissed or had resigned,
and payments that did not match grades.
</P>
<P>
He added that there were even people who did not work for the
government and had never done so but had been receiving
government allowances while there were employees of private
contractors on the government payroll.
</P>
<P>
The investigation became necessary because of the inexplicable
fluctuations in funding requirement for salaries and wages from
month to month and in view of a general perception of possible
malpractice in salary administration, Banda stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
