<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China to Auction off Wasteland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province, a leading grain producer, plans to auction off land use
rights to some of its more than 4.6 million hectares of wasteland.
</P>
<P>
The province has 8.67 million hectares of farmland, putting it
first in the country, and 3.8 million hectares of land lying idle
that could be used for agriculture, forestry, animal husbandry,
and fish.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, it developed preferential policies encouraging the
purchase of land use rights of exploitable wasteland through
public bids to speed up use of this idle resource.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government says that leases are for not less
than 30 years and not more than 70 years.
</P>
<P>
This has attracted many overseas investors and major domestic
groups to the province for wasteland development. It has leased
land use rights for 1.13 million hectares of unused wasteland, and
investors have put 500 million yuan into reclamation work to grow
grain, plant trees, and raise fish. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
