<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Birds Settle in Military Camp in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of egrets,
birds on the endangered species list, have settled in a military
camp in east China's Zhejiang Province, where they are protected
by the soldiers stationed there.
</P>
<P>
The rare birds had lost their original homes in mountain
forests as a result of the increasing illegal hunting of rare
birds and animals in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"Egrets have considerable economic value, and some criminals
tried to catch them for money making," said a soldier, adding that
since 1995, more than 200 cases involving illegal capture or
killing of egrets have been stopped.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers here say that protecting rare creatures is an
important part of environmental protection, which will greatly
benefit the future generations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
