<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Rice Technique Adds To China's Grain Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The sparse-planting rice
technique has become a major contributor to China's increased
grain production, which hit a new high of more than 490 billion kg
last year.
</P>
<P>
China will spread this new technique to about 13 million ha of
dry farmland by the end of the century, as part of the efforts to
feed its increasing population, according to the State Science and
Technology Commission.
</P>
<P>
The imported technique was first applied in south China's paddy
fields in the early 1990s, which increased rice output to 750 kg
per ha. The technique was then spread to the north and west
China's dry areas.
</P>
<P>
Chinese agronomists have improved the technique, which now
significantly reduces the amount of seed, water, labor, and
fertilizer needed.
</P>
<P>
Used on nearly 8.7 million ha of farmland in China by the end
of 1996, sparse-planting helped increase the yield of five billion
kg of grains annually over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of the paddy fields in north, northeast, and
northwest China are benefiting from the technique, which added
1,270 kg of rice output per ha while costing 300 yuan less.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels have given priority to spreading the
use of the rice planting technique. More than 80,000 training
classes were held only in 1995, involving 20 million people. This
has greatly promoted the nationwide adoption of the technique.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
