<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Invest More in Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China's largest economic center
is set to spend three percent of its gross domestic product (GDP)
on environmental protection in the remainder of the 20th century,
according to Mayor Xu Kuangdi.
</P>
<P>
This means the city would spend eight billion yuan
(about one billion US dollars) annually on environment projects, or
nearly a tenth of the country's average annual spending in the
field.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has China's largest amount of industry, and the old
141 sq. km. urban area alone has 20,000-odd workshops and more than
4,500 factories, and more than eight million residents.
</P>
<P>
The large amount of pollution, smoke, and dust from them make
pollution a serious problem in the over-crowded city, where
expansion of green space is difficult.
</P>
<P>
"Like some old European industrial cities, Shanghai has
paid a heavy price for its prosperity," said an expert here.
</P>
<P>
Since the early '90s, with the rapid growth of the economy, the
municipal government has redoubled its environmental protection
efforts. From 1991 to 1995, the city's annual spending on the
sector rose to five billion yuan, or 1.76 percent of GDP, far
greater than its original spending of less than one billion yuan
each year.
</P>
<P>
Following five years of hard work, Shanghai has managed to halt
environmental deterioration, with pollution discharges below the
1990 level while the GDP doubled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Invests More in Environmental Protection (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shanghai is determined to join the world's top
environmentally-sound cities by 2010 and to "become an
international metropolis where man will live in harmony with
the nature."
</P>
<P>
In order to do so, priority will be given to cleaning its 53-km
Suzhou River that flows through the urban area. The project will
will be completed in 15 years, at a total cost of 20 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Another 20-billion-yuan project involves a greenbelt around the
city between urban and rural areas that would cover a 7,241-ha
area, 680 ha more than the city's total green area in 1995. The
project, to be completed by 2010, will be the biggest urban
greening project in China.
</P>
<P>
The biggest problem encountered by the densely-populated city
is how to find space for nature in the downtown area. Since the
early '90s, Shanghai has been re-arranging its layout and some two
million people and 800 factories have moved out of the urban area,
a large-scale project that will continue to the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The city has used this chance to expand the green space in
the "forest of concrete buildings." In the past two years, nearly
1,000 ha of green patches have been added, and by the end of the
year, the green coverage is expected to exceed 20 percent, experts
say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0178 </DOCNO>
