<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt to Okey Rhino Gift Plan for London Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
decided to continue a plan to send two rhinos to Britain as gifts
despite strong opposition from local environmentalists, a
newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet is expect to formally endorse the decision at a
meeting Monday, Forest Minister Rameshwor Yadav was quoted by the
Kathmandu Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, Nepal pledged to give two female unicorn Indian
Rhinos to the London Zoo of Britain for the purpose of scientific
research after the Zoological Society of Britain's long pursuit
for additional rhinos for the zoo.
</P>
<P>
A local environmental group here has been trying to foil the
rhino gift plan by submitting appeal letters to Prime Minister
Lokendra Bahadur Chand and concerned ministers for scrapping the
plan.
</P>
<P>
The unicorn rhino is an endangered animal species, about which
an international convention prohibits any form of trade,
environmentalists said.
</P>
<P>
About 20 activists from the Nepal Forum of Environmental
Journalists (NFEJ) Sunday staged brief demonstrations in front of
the British Embassy and German airlines Lufthansa's office here to
protest against the decision to ship the two gift rhinos to London
via a Lufthansa scheduled flight Monday.
</P>
<P>
The environmentalist have asked the government to stop gifting
Rhinos abroad until the country has a clear and transparent policy
on such cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
