<P>
JAKARTA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- A quiet atmosphere and subdued
political activity marked the start of the election campaign in
Indonesia on Sunday, reports reaching here today from various
areas in the country indicated.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Armed Forces General Feisal Tanjung said last
night in Solo, Central Java, that Sunday's first-day election
campaign went on well and smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's three political parties -- the ruling party of
Golkar, the United Development Party (PPP) and the Indonesian
Democratic Party (PDI) kicked off the 27-day campaign for the May
29 general election at noon on Sunday with different themes.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim-based PPP came out advocating justice while the
ruling Golkar promised to eliminate poverty and the PDI said it
would uphold democracy.
</P>
<P>
Golkar Chairman Harmoko began his campaign in West Java's less
developed village of Cimara, Lebak District.
</P>
<P>
"I choose to begin my first campaign in village because more
than 70 percent of Indonesians live in rural areas. Golkar is
continuing its effort to fight poverty in the country of 200
million population," Harmoko told thousands of Golkar
sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
Golkar, which has won each of the five general elections held
since 1971, is now aiming to win 70 percent of the votes, or a
2-percent increase over its share at the 1992 election when the
PPP received 19 percent and the PDI 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
PDI Chairman Soerjadi, who began his campaign in Pontianak,
West Kalimantan, said his party has high motivation to struggle
for the people's aspirations and uphold democracy in the country.
 The implementation of national development has successfully
improved the people's welfare, but it also has widened the gap
between the rich and the poor, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The rich is getting richer and the poor is getting poorer," he
was quoted by the official Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PPP Chairman Ismal Hasan Metareum, who kicked off
his election campaign in Medan, North Sumatra, said his party has
always fought for justice, truth and honesty.
</P>
<P>
The people are entitled to express political aspirations, to do
business, to enjoy education and to feel secure, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed to raise the educational budget to amount to
at least 20 percent of the state budget.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there were some small clashes reported in Medan,
Yogjakarta and Solo, Central Java, but no death or material losses
occurred in the incidents, except three PPP supporters suffering
light injuries.
</P>
<P>
The election campaign will run until May 23 before a five-day
"cooling-off period," when campaigning is banned, and the poll on
May 29.
</P>
<P>
The country's nearly 124 million eligible voters will elect 425
candidates to the 500-seat parliament. The remaining 75 seats are
reserved for the Armed Forces which does not vote.
</P>
<P>
In this year's campaign, the country is divided into three
groups of campaign areas with Group I covering Sumatra, Nusa
Tenggara and East Timor; Group II covering Java, Maluku and Irian
Jaya; and Group III covering Kalimantan and Sulawesi.
</P>
<P>
On the first day, Golkar campaigned in Group II while the PPP
and the PDI campaigned in Group I and III respectively. All the
contestants will get their turn in the three groups in the coming
days in according with the election rules.
</P>
<P>
Almost 50 percent or 216 of the parliamentary seats are
reserved for Java whose population is about 117 million.
</P>
<P>
As the country's three parties began their election campaigns,
security in Indonesia's capital and other key areas has been
tightened.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta Military Command Chief of General Staff Brig. Gen.
Sjafrie Syamsoedin said the police would deploy 19,000 members who
would be assisted by some 7,700 Armed Forces troops.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
