<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Houston Festival Ends with Chinese Culture Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The 26th Houston International
Festival today closed with Chinese culture honored in the Southern
U.S. city.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that the Houston International Festival
was held with a spotlight on Chinese culture since it started in
1972.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 Chinese artists performed acrobatics and folk
arts, and played traditional Chinese music instruments. Their
performances in the festival, the amazing Chinese acrobatics in
particular, were warmly applauded by visitors.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Village has become a unique living museum featuring
the sights, sounds and aromas of both ancient and modern Chinese
culture, attracting thousands of people every day.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese acrobatics also gave performances in many schools
of the city to introduce Chinese culture to U.S. students to
promote mutual understanding between two peoples.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 artists from around the world displayed their
handmade arts and crafts in several art markets, and gave modern
and folk performances in many music stages.
</P>
<P>
The Houston International Festival, which opened on April 18,
attracted more than 1 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
