<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rios Claims Monte Carlo Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Marcelo Rios defeated Alex Corretja
6-4, 6-3, 6-3 Sunday to win the Monte Carlo Open, stopping a
Sanish run in clay court tournaments.
</P>
<P>
Rios will move to No. 8 in the rankings and took away 337,000
U.S. dollars with the victory.
</P>
<P>
The 2-hour, 14-minute final was marked by steady but
unspectacular tennis as the players barely approached the net. But
Rios was ahead from the start.
</P>
<P>
Spaniards, including Corretja two weeks ago at Estoril,
Portugal, had won the first two clay court tournaments of the
season.
</P>
<P>
Rios, as with other Monte Carlo winners, much now be one of the
favorites for the French Open, which begins May 26 and highlights
the clay-court season.
</P>
<P>
Pete Sampras has won the last two Grand Slams _ the Australian
Open and and U.S. Open _ but lost his first match in Monte Carlo.
Corretja pushed Sampras to a five sets at last year's U.S. Open
but was no match for Rios on clay.
</P>
<P>
The tournament lost 10 of the top 16 players by the second
round, with Sampras, Boris Becker and three-time champion Thomas
Muster eliminated in one afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Before the final, the 100th anniversary of the tournament was
celebrated with a number of former champions, including Bjorn Borg
and Andrei Chesnokov on crutches. Chesnokov broke his leg on court
during a match in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
