<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 300,000 Sri Lankan Displaced Persons Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 28 (Xinhua) -- More than 300,000 displaced Sri
Lankans have so far returned to their homes in the Jaffna
Peninsula from areas held by Tamil rebels, according to military
sources here today.
</P>
<P>
Out of the estimated 500,000 displaced following military
operations in the peninsula last year, a steady flow of about 500
persons daily has been recorded to return to the peninsula from
the rebels-controlled areas, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 90,000 others have moved to
locations in the south and that only 110,000 are continuing to be
held captive in rebel-held areas.
</P>
<P>
Those who have returned to the peninsula said they had to
suffer untold hardships while in rebel-held territory where there
was a severe shortage of food and other essentials including safe
drinking water, the sources stated.
</P>
<P>
The sources noted that whatever food items and medicines were
sent to these areas for refugees by the government were captured
by the rebels for their own use.
</P>
<P>
The Jaffna Peninsula, once the stronghold of the Tamil rebels,
who have waged a 14-year war for a separate state in the north and
east of the country, was recaptured by government troops last May.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
