<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stable Land Contract System Called for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Wen Jiabao, an alternate member
of the Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee, said that the farmland contract system in rural China
needs to remain stable for a long time.
</P>
<P>
This has been demanded by farmers and has been the policy of
the Party Central Committee, Wen said while addressing a recent
conference on rural work.
</P>
<P>
Today's "People's Daily carried part of Wen's speech at the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The land contract system will remain unchanged for 15
years, he said, and will be renewed for another 30 years.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, the land contract system has remained stable, but
there are problems that should be brought to people's attention,
he said. Only half of China's villages, for example, have
continueed the land contract system, and there are even fewer that
have extended the contracts to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
And some places have recalled land that had already been
contracted out to farmers, using various excuses, he added, noting
that these run counter to farmers' wishes and are incompatible
with the Party Central Committee policies.
</P>
<P>
If this continues to spread, it will not only dampen farmers'
initiative, but will also impede production in rural areas and
even destroy whatever progress has been made in rural reforms, Wen
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Land used for production cannot avoid changing hands. But these
exchanges should be based on farmers' desires rather than on
administrative orders, he said.
</P>
<P>
The use of land will ultimately lead to farming on a fairly
large scale, which is in accordance with rural development trends,
Wen said, but this requires a long period of development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
