<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (49-50) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (49-50) in
a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Why should not Hong Kong change into a political city?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Hong Kong has never been a country but a region. It has
never been a political city but a free port. Its advantages lie in
its economy. Thanks to the efforts of several generations of the
local people, Hong Kong has become one of the world's economic,
trade, financial and shipping centres.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing the fact that Hong Kong is an economic city and
endeavoring to maintain its status as an economic city -- this is
an attitude of being genuinely responsible for Hong Kong and the
interests of the Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
By opposing attempts to change Hong Kong into a political city,
we mean that Hong Kong should not be changed into an arena of
fierce rivalry among international political forces and into a
base for activities against the central government. Otherwise,
Hong Kong would lose its advantages.
</P>
<P>
Question: What are the nature and functions of district
organizations of the Hong Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: District organizations refer to the city administration
council, district administrations, district legislatures and other
district organizations.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, district organizations are not
organs of political power and may be established in the Hong Kong
SAR. District organizations will be consulted by the government of
the Hong Kong SAR on district administration and other affairs, or
be responsible for providing services in such fields as culture,
recreation and environmental sanitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Applicants Vie to Fill Vacant Posts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Sufang has given exams to
her students for 14 years. She was a bit nervous on Saturday when
she was taking a test.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, 37, was one of nearly 300 competitors taking the final
oral exam to quality for one of Beijing's 57 intermediate-level
official vacancies.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased that the selection method has changed from
official appointment to open application. I'd like to take on a
tougher job," said Zhang, deputy director of a college department.
</P>
<P>
She had applied for the post of vice-chairman of the national
and overseas Chinese affairs committee under the Beijing Municipal
People's Congress, the local legislator, according to a report in
today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Her fellow competitors, most of them between 36 and 45, had
college education background, and 33 percent had their master's or
doctoral degrees.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the candidates had been serving as division
chiefs for more than three years and 40 percent have been division
deputy chiefs for more than five years, the report said.
</P>
<P>
They were among 1,631 people who applied for the posts and took
written examinations on general knowledge in March.
</P>
<P>
The candidates answered 16 questions from seven-person panels
comprising municipal government officials and experts from
institutes and universities.
</P>
<P>
Almost all of the 150 examiners were college graduates; about
80 percent ranked above bureau deputy chief.
</P>
<P>
Two people will be chosen from the competitors for each post
following the oral test. After careful consideration, one will
fill the vacancy in June, the report said.
</P>
<P>
All 57 will work for one year on a trial basis. Any who fail to
prove themselves will be removed from their posts, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Recruiting large number of intermediate ranking officials
through open exams in Beijing will have a considerable impact on
recruiting systems across the country," said 39-year-old Wang
Aimin, who was the first to apply to take the examination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
