<HEADLINE> Public Transportation To Get Priority in Chinese Cities (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government plans to
give priority to developing public transportation in all large and
medium-sized cities to deal with worsening traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
Special bus lanes will be set aside this year in the cities of
Beijing, Dalian, and Shenyang, the capital of northeast China's
Liaoning Province, and in Kunming, the capital of Yunnan
Province, Zhang Kuichang, director of the Urban Construction
Department of the Ministry of Construction, said here today.
</P>
<P>
"After we acquire enough experience to deal with these lanes,
we'll open similar lanes in many other cities," Zhang told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
A special bus lane will first be provided along the
five-km-long Chang'an Avenue, the Chinese capital's No 1 downtown
arterial, by no later than June 30, sources from the Beijing
Municipal Public Security Traffic Administration say.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Construction expects buses, taxis, and subways
to handle more than a third of transportation by the end of the
century, meaning a fairly reasonable level of public
transportation.
</P>
<P>
To do this, the capacity of public transportation will have to
be more than double the 1996's figure, Zhang noted.
</P>
<P>
Urban residents in China went out for travel 150 billion times
in 1996, but the public transport system could handle only 28
billion passengers a year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese cities have an increasing number of traffic
jams. According to a recent survey by the Ministry of Public
Security's Public Traffic Administration, the average speed of
motor vehicles has dropped to 13 km per hour in large cities, from
nearly 20 km per hour in the early 1980s, and the figure for buses
is now less than ten kw per hour.
</P>
<P>
"If no measures are taken, traffic in the metropolises of
Beijing, Shanghai, and Chongqing will be at a standstill in no
more than a decade," Zhang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Transportation to Get Priority in Chinese Cities (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Quan pointed out that measures should be taken to support
public transportation, instead of depending only on special bus lanes.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Ministry of Construction, Beijing
has decided to put 200 more buses into use this year, while
Shanghai will add 600 new air-conditioned buses. Other large and
medium-sized cities, such as Chongqing, Guangzhou, Nanjing, and
Xi'an, will also increase the use of these vehicles this year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Ministry is considering introducing a ticket
price adjustment mechanism for public transportion nationwide,
where ticket prices could be adjusted according to the increase in
average salaries and wages.
</P>
<P>
The effort is expected to help many loss-making enterprises and
to arouse employee initiative, said Zhang Kuichang, a Ministry
official.
</P>
<P>
Li Jianguo, a public transportation expert, suggests the public
transportation and motor vehicle fuel be taxed to increase funds
for public transportation. Government policies should also
encourage companies and foreign business people to get involved in
the public transportation sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Transportation to Get Priority in Chinese Cities (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Road construction has accelerated in recent years, and per
capita road availability was 7.3 square meters by the end of last
year, and the figure for Beijing, Shanghai, and Tianjin was more
than 5 sq.m. The increased use of motor vehicles, however has
caused severe problems.
</P>
<P>
It is a fact of life in all cities that road construction
cannot keep pace with the increase in the number of motor
vehicles, says Li Jianguo, director of the Beijing Municipal
Public Traffic Research Office.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the only way out is to give priority to the
development of the public transport system.
</P>
<P>
One sq m of roads treavelled by buses can handle 10 to 15
times that of cars in an hour, Li explains.
</P>
<P>
In fact, it is also impossible over a long period of time for
private automobiles to play a major role in a populous country
like China, whose GDP can only reach 3.8 trillion US dollars by
2010, a per capita GDP of about 2,700 US dollars, meaning that
most Chinese families still can not afford cars.
</P>
<P>
China now produces some 350,000 cars annually, and imports
several thousand, too small a figure for the more than 300 million
families in the country.
</P>
<P>
In the long run, the way to establish a good pattern of urban
traffic is to develop subways and buses because of their advantage
in saving time, punctuality, large handling capacity, and safety,
according to Quan Yongshen, vice-president of the Beijing
Municipal City Planning and Design Institute.
</P>
<P>
Chinese cities, however, cannot afford to build a large number
of subways. One km of subways now costs 600 to 800 million yuan
(70-100 million US dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
