<HEADLINE> Guangdong Fair To Spur Guangxi's Exports In 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing Chinese Export
Commodities Fair in Guangzhou is expected to pave the way for a
rebound of foreign trade in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region,
today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing based newspaper also says that by April 21, the 71
stands from Guangxi's 60 foreign trade enterprises had concluded
deals worth over 30 million US dollars, up three percent from the
same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Deals involving foodstuffs and specialties topped the
transaction pile with the volume exceeding 15 million US
dollars. Deals involving garments and knitwear surpassed six
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Guangxi trading delegation signed deals worth over eight
million US dollars with the European Union, over five million US
dollars with the United States, over 4.7 million US dollars with
Southeast Asian countries and over 3.4 million US dollars with
Hong Kong and Macao within the first five days.
</P>
<P>
The paper quotes Li Manying, deputy director of the Guangxi
Regional Department of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation as
saying that the Guangxi trading delegation is expecting to top its
transaction target of 150 million US dollars during the fair.
</P>
<P>
Trade with Southeast Asian countries has been standing at about
20 percent of Guangxi's total in the past few years. The region's
exports are expected to rise from last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Guangxi's foreign trade was valued at 2.8 billion US
dollars, with exports making up 1.9 billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
