<HEADLINE> Shanghai Real Estate Trade Center Eases Property Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Real Estate Trading
Center is ready to help raise the market out of its current slump
by providing computerized trading and other services for buyers,
sellers and investors, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing based newspaper quotes Liu Daotong, director of the
center, as saying that the center was established under a municipal
government plan to promote the secondary trading of properties,
expand market size and increase the proportion of the real estate
industry in the city's gross domestic products.
</P>
<P>
The center will publish land supply and market supply figures
and list sales and prices of different types of housing. It will
help to set up market forecasting and supervisory systems.
</P>
<P>
Real estate traders will be computerized at the center, which
will link market activities in 20 Shanghai districts and counties
by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Located inside the Shanghai Municipal Housing and Land
Administration building in Pudong's Lujiazui area, the center has
offered 34 seats to a select number of real estate developers and
intermediate brokerage firms out of a total more than 5,000.
</P>
<P>
Liu said standardizing market behaviour is the first step
Shanghai must take to promote sales and make real estate one of
the city's economic pillars. Real estate data and analyses will be
made available once a month in the initial state and more
frequently in the future.
</P>
<P>
Apart from information and trading, the center also provides
management of property transfers, mortgages, leasing and
intermediate transaction services.
</P>
<P>
The center will be connected to the Internet, allowing
investors in Hong Kong, Taiwan and Singapore to trade by opening
outlets linked to networks there. Buyers of Shanghai real estate
outside the Chinese mainland are from Hong Kong, Taiwan and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai offers an average of two million square meters of
housing to overseas investors annually. The paper says.

nnnn
</P>
