<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Beats Finland at World Ice Hockey Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic, backed by
Martin Prochazka's two goals, edged Finland 2-1 Sunday in the
second match to defend its title at the world ice hockey
championship.
</P>
<P>
The Czech, who beat Germany 2-1 Saturday, rallied to snatch its
second one-goal victory.
</P>
<P>
Mika Nieminen opened the scoring for the Finns but Prochazka
equalised with less than a minute to go in the first
period. Prochazka scored the winner in the 42nd minute.
</P>
<P>
The Czechs rest on Monday and Tuesday and play Slovakia on
Wednesday and Russia on Thursday in A Pool matches.
</P>
<P>
After two games, the Czechs top the A Pool standings with a
perfect 2-0 and have gone 10 games, stretching back to the 1995
championships, without a loss.
</P>
<P>
In day's other A Pool action in Helsinki, Russia took a 1-0
lead after 16 seconds but had to come back to earn a 2-2 tie with
Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
In B Pool action, Olympic champions Sweden scored twice in each
of the first two periods and added three more in the third to down
Canada 7-2.
</P>
<P>
Sweden took advantage of some undisciplined play by Canada to
climb to the top of the B Pool standings with an 2-0 record.
</P>
<P>
The United States, looking for its first title in 64 years,
also needed a late third period goal to squeeze past Latvia 5-4 in
its opener. 
</P>
</TEXT>
