<HEADLINE> Ad Companies Shut down for Illegal Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Fifty advertising companies were
closed last Thursday to protect consumers' interests in Xi'an, the
capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
A one-month advertising crackdown found the 50 companies were
paying commissions or doing business as "briefcase firms" without
capital, offices or skilled personnel.
</P>
<P>
This seriously disturbed the order of the advertising market,
according to Bai Shuyou, an official with the Xi'an City
Industrial and Commercial Administration.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid development of the advertising industry, Xi'an
boasted 576 advertising companies with more than 5,000 employees
by the end of 1996. The industry's total annual turnover reached
250 million yuan (30 million US dollars), Bai said.
</P>
<P>
However, some did not abide by the law. The local industrial
and commercial administration started regular examination of the
industry last month and decided to cancel the qualification of
those 50 companies, Bai said.
</P>
<P>
And the local administration also fined a Shenzhen company
which illegally advertised and sold a product. The authorities
confiscated the product, valued at three million yuan (about
361,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The local administration hopes to keep order and promote the
healthy development of the advertising industry by strict controls
and active promotion, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
