<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reshuffle Auto Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 28 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government plans to
trim the number of domestic automobile plants from 120 to
six. Around 2010 the car manufactures will be further reorganized
into three auto giants, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing based newspaper also says that China now has 126
auto manufacturing plants, more than 600 refitting factories and
more than 4,000 spare parts factories. Most of the factories
operate on a small scale, with some having an annual output of
less than 10,000 units.
</P>
<P>
China's automobile industry has for years been sluggish,
disorderly and inefficient as regards its development. Despite
having the largest number of factories, in 1995, China had a total
output of only 1.5 million units.
</P>
<P>
As a result of neglecting the growing demand for light trucks
and cars, Chinese light truck manufacturing plants popped up all
over the country, accounting for half of the total number of car
assembly plants. Millions of foreign cars were imported, and the
amount spent on importing the cars was three times the total
government investment in the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
China will adjust the dispersed production pattern in order to
manufacture cars in batches. In the 1996-2000 period, China plans
to invest 12 billion US dollars to develop its eight main car and
mini-car manufacturers, including the three major car producers
- Shanghai Volkswagen, First Automotive Works-Volkswagen and Wuhan
Shenlong.
</P>
<P>
Because imports have squeezed the Chinese auto industry, it
might be best for China to concentrate on developing car
components. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Book on Male Reproductive Science Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 28 (Xinhua) -- China's first medical work on male
reproductive science has been published here to spread health care
education among men.
</P>
<P>
Some 59 experts and professors nationwide co-wrote the book,
Clinical Male Science, which explains in detail the structure and
pathology of man's reproductive organs and related diseases.
</P>
<P>
Compared to gynecology, male reproductive science has been a
relatively unexplored field in China, drawing attention from
researchers worldwide as recently as the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
It focuses on the study of male's reproductive system,
sterility and venereal diseases.
</P>
<P>
China has made great progress in the field over the past ten
years.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Chairman of Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress Wu Jieping, who first called for research on the subject,
named the book. He is also an academician with the Chinese Academy
of Sciences and the Chinese Academy of Engineering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
