<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-7 Finance Leaders Hint to Intervene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The G-7 most industrial
nations today hinted that they would take neccesary measures to
dump billions of dollars on exchange markets if the upswinging
U.S. dollars doesn't stabilize.
</P>
<P>
Following their five-hour closed-door meeting, the finance
ministers and central bank presidents of the Britain, Canada,
France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States issued a
statement. They said in the statement, "We discussed developments
in exchange and financial markets since our last meeting in Berlin
where we note that major misalignments in exchange markets had
been corrected. We agreed that exchange rates should reflect
economic fundamentals and that excess volatility and significant
deviation from fundamentals are undersirable."
</P>
<P>
"In this context," the statement added, "we emphasized the
importance of avoiding exchange rates that could lead to the
reemergence of large external imbalances. We agreed to monitor
developments and to cooperate in exchange markets."
</P>
<P>
Prior to the G-7 meeting, U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
had a separate meeting with his Japanese counterpart Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka. The two sides "reaffirmed their commitment to
cooperate closely in exchange markets as appropriate."
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, as the yen dropped to a 4-year low against the
dollar, Japanese officials signaled that they were prepared to
intervene to stop the yen's deterioration.
</P>
<P>
However, up to now, the U.S. side has refused to discuss
publicly the possibility of the United States joining any
intervention.
</P>
<P>
When the G-7 ministers last met in Berlin in February, they
noticed that the dollar's nearly two-year recovery from a
post-World War II low of 80 yen had gone far enough.
</P>
<P>
At that time, the dollar had rebounded about 50 percent against
the yen and 25 percent against the German mark. Since then, it has
pushed up 3 percent to 4 percent and traded at 126.25 yen late
Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Seven also discussed ways to back growth in the
poorest developing countries and reduce the risk of another
financial crisis such as the collapse of the Mexican peso in late
1994.
</P>
<P>
The participants expressed their support for the resumption
this month of financial service negotiations in the World Trade
Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
