<HEADLINE> Tourism Facilities Improvement in Central Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 28 (Xinhua) -- Zhangjiajie, a well-known
tourist area in the western part of Hunan Province in central
China, has spent more than four billion yuan on basic facilities
since 1988.
</P>
<P>
The Zhangjiajie Airport has opened air routes to a dozen large
and medium-sized cities including Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou,
Xiamen and Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
The airport now handles 230,000 people a year. The number of
flights is 45 in the summertime, a brisk season for the local
tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Express trains from the city now go to Guangzhou, Beijing, and
Changsha, and another train is expected for Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiajie now has more than 700 hotels with a total of 30,000
beds, including 21 hotels that cater to overseas visitors and five
star-rated hotels.
</P>
<P>
The city was visited by more than 1.8 million foreign and
domestic tourists last year, with tourism earnings reaching 450
million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
