<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Women Get An Upper Hand of Europeans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 27 (Xinhua) -- Asian women
spearheaded by the mighty Chinese underlined their prowess as they
swept three team semi-final berths at the World Table Tennis
Championships here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
China, South Korea and the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea romped into the last four with the remaining berth going to
Germany, which outlasted Sweden in five games.
</P>
<P>
China's world No. 1 Deng Yaping paced the defending champion to
a 3-0 victory of Hong Kong, third-place finisher at the last world
championships.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Deng, two-time double gold medalist in the 1992
and 1996 Olympic Games, combined her usual array of table tennis
wares to deadly effect, beating Wong Ching 21-13, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
Fifth-ranked Li Ju snatched the second rubber, nipping Hong
Kong's top player Cha Po Wa 21-15, 21-15, and fourth-rated Yang
Ying sealed the victory with a three-set win over Song Ah Sim.
</P>
<P>
Yang, 19, showed nerves midway in her game as she squandered
seven match points to lose the second set 22-24.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese penhold fast attacker turned up the heat in the
third set, beating Song 21-14.
</P>
<P>
DPR Korea trounced Romania 3-0 to join South Korea in the medal
contention.
</P>
<P>
South Korea reached the semi-finals at the expense of Japan,
whose top player Koyama Chire snatched two points but couldn't
prevent the elimination.
</P>
<P>
China takes on Germany and Romania plays South Korea in the
semi-finals on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A scenario that the Chinese men's team hoped to avoid is set to
happen as both Sweden and South Korea were drawn against China in
the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
"That is the worst situation that could happen to the Chinese
team," said team leader Li Furong. "We hoped that China wouldn't
meet Sweden and South Korea too early, but the draw is beyond our
expectation."
</P>
<P>
Sweden and South Korea both failed to win their groups and thus
lost their seeding in the quarter-finals. Only the winners of
elite Group A to D were seeded in the last eight.
</P>
<P>
The other group winners who went directly into the last eight
were Japan, Germany and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Sweden had met China six times for the last seven world
championship finals with each winning three.
</P>
<P>
"I will be very happy if Sweden reaches the final," said Ulf
Carlsson, who took the helm of an aging Swedish team after head
coach Soren Allen resigned last year.
</P>
<P>
"That will be a bonus If we win the championship," he added.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has beaten China twice in less than six
months. After a 3-0 defeat of the Chinese team led by world
champion Kong Linghui and Olympic champion Liu Guoliang in the
Asian championships in December last year, South Korea edged out
their longtime rival 3-2 in the Qatar Open in February.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
