<DOCNO> XIE19970428.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-24 Considers Holding Summit Dialogue with G-7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 27 (Xinhua) -- The G-24 developing countries
are considering a certain sort of summit dialogue with the G-7
most industrial countries, said Antonio Casas Gonzalez, Chairman
of the Intergovernmental Group of 24 on International Monetary
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Gonzalez, who is also President of Venezuela's Central Bank,
made the announcement at a press conference after concluding the
56th Ministerial meeting at the headquarters of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said a technical group, which includes some G-24 and G-7
countries, will be set up to study the possibility of the summit,
but it is too early to tell the concrete plan for such dialogue.
</P>
<P>
A communique, issued after the meeting, said that the Ministers
noted that the world economy continues to grow at a steady pace
with low inflation. For the fifth year in a row, the developing
countries have led in the contributions to world economic growth.
</P>
<P>
While overall prospects appear positive, it noted, the current
improvement in Sub-Saharan Africa must be viewed with caution, in
the light of the projected decline in non-fuel commodity prices,
shrinking official development assistance (ODA) and the
relatively low level of foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that although flows of private resources to
less developed countries are expanding, they continue to be
channeled to only a few countries.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the G-24 ministers also showed their
concern over ODA which is showing a disturbing downward trend with
the year 1996 seeing the lowest level in a decade.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the critical role of such assistance for the poorest
nations, the ministers noted that private capital flows are no
substitute for official flows which could help facilitate growth
and alleviate poverty in these countries.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 Ministers will meet again in Hong Kong on September
20, this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
